<HEADLINE> Lukashenko: Russia Ignores Minsk' Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko said Wednesday that he had urged Russian President
Boris Yeltsin not to pull out nuclear weapons from Belarus hastily
but Yeltsin ignored his suggestion.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said he had warned Yeltsin that once the nuclear
weapons were out of Belarus, Eastern European countries would join
NATO. The last strategic nuclear missile left Belarus for Russia
in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Real life has shown that this is exactly what happened; as
soon as the missiles were withdrawn, Eastern Europe joined NATO,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Like Russia, Belarus is bitterly against the transatlantic
alliance's eastward enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said that at the time he had been under considerable
pressure from "(U.S. President Bill) Clinton on one side and
Yeltsin on the other," the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He also complained that Russia ignored his appeals for a joint
policy toward NATO. "The result was military intervention by the
alliance in the Balkans."
</P>
<P>
"Maybe tomorrow you'll invite (Semyon) Sharetsky (former
Belarus parliamentary speaker in opposition to Lukashenko) to
Moscow as you've done (Montenegrin President Milo) Djukanovic?"
Lukashenko said in a barely veiled criticism of Russia's perceived
closer ties with Montenegro away from Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
"Where are the guarantees (that this will not happen)?" he
asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
