<HEADLINE> Relief Food Delivered to Besieged Angolan City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of urgently
needed relief food are being distributed to thousands of starving
people in the war-torn city of Malange in Angola, according to a
news released issued by the U.N. World Food Program (WFP).
</P>
<P>
The release available here Wednesday said that WFP staff, who
visited the besieged city last week, described the situation there
as "critical" with an estimated three to four people dying of
hunger each day.
</P>
<P>
The batch of some 245 tons of food arrived in the city by road
last week was given to non-governmental organizations there for
immediate distribution to child centers and a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
Francesco Strippoli, WFP Representative and Humanitarian Aid
Coordinator in Angola, was quoted as saying that "we plan to
transport a further 2,200 tons of food to Malange through August
but security is still very bad, both on the road and in the city."
</P>
<P>
Malange, like several other Angolan cities, has been under
continuous attack by the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) rebel forces in recent months, making it
impossible to deliver food either by air or road, according to
WFP.
</P>
<P>
At present, the WFP can deliver some 7,000 tons of food per
month, but in order to feed all Angolans, it would need to double
the supplies to 130, 000 tons a month, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
