<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Publish Anti-Malaria Guideline Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Health Ministry
has worked out a new guideline enabling the country to identify
and control malaria epidemic, the Ethiopian News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The guideline is designed to create conducive situations to
prevent malaria before the epidemic goes out of control, Daniel
Kebede, representative of malaria and other vector-borne diseases
control team, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The guideline, soon to be distributed to the various state
health bureaus, would also enable the public at large to actively
participate in the fight against the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaria is a common disease in many parts of Ethiopia. Health
authorities in the country have been observing an anti-malaria
week for years to raise public awareness on malaria control
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide campaign is normally held from August 24 to 30
as August is a month suitable for malaria breeding in most parts
of the Horn of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
Beginning from early this month, anti-malaria chemicals are
being sprayed in parts of the country to preempt possible outbreak
of the epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
