<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Language Will Become More Important: German Scholar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese language will become a
more important speech for international communication, and in
future, Chinese will be taught in German schools as a normal
foreign language just like English and French, a German linguistic
scholar said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"In 10 or 20 years, Chinese will be counted as a normal foreign
language (in Germany)," Professor Peter Kupfer was quoted as
telling the Deutsche Presse Agentur (DPA) news agency. Kupfer is a
professor at University Mainz and chairman of Germany's Chinese
Language Professional Association.
</P>
<P>
According to Kupfer, who is due to host the Sixth International
Symposium for Chinese as Foreign Language, more German schools are
providing with Chinese language courses in recent years. The
symposium will begin on August 8 in the city of Hannover.
</P>
<P>
The ground for this development, said Kupfer, is the fast
expanding Sino-German ties, especially in economic fields.
</P>
<P>
"The language will creep into Germans' daily life gradually,
for example, through symbols written in Chinese inside an imported
refrigerator made in China," the professor said.
</P>
<P>
About 400 delegates from 35 countries are expected to take part
in the symposium, the first one ever to be held outside China.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, organized by the Chinese Language Professional
Association and China's International Society of Chinese Language
Teaching, is to show that a real understanding over the Chinese
culture and society is possible only with an understanding over
the Chinese language, said the German host to the symposium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
