<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Holds Science, Technology Symposium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The sixth symposium on science and
 technology of Zimbabwe opened in Harare Wednesday to seek
solutions to the country's socio-economic problems through
research.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwe's Vice-President Simon
Muzenda appealed to the scientific community to find solutions to
the country's socio-economic problems through research.
</P>
<P>
He reassured the participants that the government was making
efforts to increase its funding for scientific research.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda said a bio-safety board had been formed to monitor
ethical problems, dangers and risks associated with bio-technology
such as the release of genetically modified organisms.
</P>
<P>
A food and nutrition council had also been set up to prepare
for the new challenges in the next millennium, he added.
</P>
<P>
A radiation and protection agency was under consideration and a
Zimbabwe Academic and Research Network was being installed, the
vice-president noted.
</P>
<P>
Muzenda took a swipe at the media for singling out Zimbabwe as
a country mostly affected by the AIDS pandemic in the world. He
called on the scientific community to continue searching for a
cure or vaccine.
</P>
<P>
About 200 experts attended the symposium which was organized by
the Research Council of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme is "a century of science and technology --
challenges for the next millennium". 
</P>
</TEXT>
