<HEADLINE> Albright Says No Plan to Delay Mideast Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has not decided to postpone her trip to the
Middle East this month despite there are differences between
Israel and the Palestinians over the implementation of the Wye
agreement, the State Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There's been no decision to delay the trip," spokesman James
Rubin told reporters. "We indicated that we expected to travel
this month and that remains our expectation."
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post and Na'aretz newspapers reported Wednesday
that Albright might postpone the trip due to disappointment over a
proposal by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak to postpone the
implementation of the Wye agreement until Oct. 1, which was flatly
rejected by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first trip by Albright to the Middle East
since last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
