<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt exports 90 percent of its 110,000 tons of carbon
black annually, yielding a revenue of 160 million Egyptian pounds
(47.1 million U.S. dollars), an official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Authority for Investment and Free Zones Ibrahim
Fawzi said the production of carbon black will rise to 180,000
tons when the fourth phase of a project in the Egyptian port city
of Alexandria is completed next year.
</P>
<P>
At that time, Egypt, which began to develop the industry in
1994, will become the world's largest producer of carbon black,
the country's Middle East News Agency quoted Fawzi as saying.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Over one million tourists visited Morocco during
the first six months of this year, up by 164 percent as compared
to the corresponding period of 1998, said a report by the Moroccan
Tourism Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The tourists are mostly from France, Britain, the Benelux
countries (namely, Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg) and
North America, the Alam Al Yom newspaper quoted the report as
saying.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Kuwaiti Parliament on Tuesday approved a
4.25 billion dinars (some 14 billion U.S. dollars) budget for the
fiscal year 1999/2000 starting on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was passed by a vote of 27-20 with one
abstention, projected state revenues at 2.224 billion dinars (some
7.339 billion dollars), and a deficit at 2.026 billion dinars
(6.685 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues were estimated at 1.761 billion dinars (5.811
billion dollars) and non-oil income at 463 million dinars (1.527
billion dollars), compared with 1.894 billion dinars (6.25 billion
dollars) and non-oil income of 550 million dinars (1.815 billion
dollars) for the past year respectively.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Trade volume between Egypt and the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) is expected to reach one
billion U.S. dollars this year, said Egyptian Minister of Trade
and Supply Ahmed Gowaili Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili made the remark on the occasion of inaugurating the
first regular maritime line to east Africa, the Cairo-based Al
Ahram newspaper reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
