<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Champ Waldner Struggles in Second Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion
Jan-Ove Waldner seemed not in his best form as he edged out unknown
Sergei Andrianov in the men's singles second round of the world table
tennis championships here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Swede conceded the third set and nearly lost the
fourth in his 21-17, 21-18, 18-21, 23-21 win over the Russian
qualifier.
</P>
<P>
Andrianov, undaunted facing the arguably the best ever player in
the world, hit a lot of forehand and backhand winners in the third set
while the Swede seemed to lose concentration.
</P>
<P>
Waldner led all the way in the fourth round until he served the
ball into the net to see the score tied at 21-21. Then two wayward
shots by the Russian sent Waldner into the third round.
</P>
<P>
Waldner has won so many titles that he lost count. In last world
championships, Waldner routed Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus to win
his second world singles championship since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The immensely talented Swede is the only player in the world to
have won a "Grand Slam" of the Olympic, world championship and World
Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 and top seed Samsonov also made the third round after
thumping Frenchman Nicolas Chatelain 21-19, 21-13, 21-12.
</P>
<P>
Dual Olympic champion Liu Guoliang's deceptively spinning serves
and follow-up attacks were just too much for Tho Von Scheele who lost
21-8, 22-20, 21-3.
</P>
<P>
Liu's Olympic doubles champion partner Kong Linghui also cruised
into the third round, beating South Korean Park Sang Joon 21-10,
21-8, 21-10.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Wang Liqin moved up with 22-20, 21-12, 21-12 thrashing of
Russian Andrei Mazunov.
</P>
<P>
Two-time World Cup winner Zoran Primorac of Croatia rallied to
subdue Frenchman Michel Martinez 16-21, 21-15, 21-14, 21-19, while
current World Cup runner-up Kim Taek Soo of South Korea nipped
Sweden's Fredri Hakansson 14-21, 21-7, 21-14, 21-19.
</P>
<P>
In the women's third round, top seed and World Cup holder Wang
Nan of China overcame Melissa Muller of the Netherlands 21-14,
21-11, 21-5.
</P>
<P>
The other victorious Chinese women were Cheng Hongxia, Zhang
Yining, Yang Ying, Lin Ling, Li Nan, Wang Hui, Sun Jin and Li Ju.
</P>
</TEXT>
