<HEADLINE> Nigeria May Deploy Troops to Combat Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Following rising violent crimes
like armed robberies and assassinations nationwide, Nigerian
government may shortly deploy troops to some of the country's
states to stem the trend, according to a Nigerian newspaper
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Indications to this emerged yesterday as the police redeployed
its commissioners, assistant commissioners of police, chief
superintendent of police and 105 other officers in an apparent
attempt to curb the increasing violent crimes, reported This Day,
a major Nigerian daily.
</P>
<P>
Government is said to believe that the crime wave, which has
seen prominent citizens like renowned industrialist Chris
Ogunbajo, Presidential Adviser Alhaji Mahmud Wazri, former Sports
Minister Anthony Ikhazobh and others becoming victims, can no
longer be managed by ordinary policing methods.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a president source as saying that
President Olusegun Obasanjo may have been seriously considering
the option of bringing in the troops at least temporarily, at the
request of some state governors with whom he extensively spoke on
telephone.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the National Security Council will also discuss
the activity of armed bandits in the North-south and North-west
who launch cross border raids into Nigeria maiming and killing
villagers in those areas.
</P>
<P>
Source said that the activities of menacing secret cults who
recently killed four students of the Obafemi Awolowo University
at IleIfe would also be discussed by the council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
