<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt-Libya Summit Discuss Regional Issues, Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
met on Wednesday with visiting Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in
the Mediterranean town of Mersa Matrouh, 550 kilometers northwest
of Cairo, to discuss regional issues and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Egyptian Information
Minister Safwat el-Sherif said the two leaders dealt with key Arab
issues and efforts to clear Arab atmospheres and boost joint Arab
action, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed the Arab-African relations and
Libya's efforts to convene an extraordinary African summit in
Tripoli next month, el-Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
The talks dealt with the two North African neighbors' efforts
to seek ways of helping Sudan end the 16-year-old civil war and
reach national reconciliation, the Egyptian minister added.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's opposition National Democratic Alliance ended a
five-day meeting in Tripoli on Sunday. The alliance groups
northern Sudanese parties that are seeking democracy and the Sudan
People's Liberation Army, which has been fighting for autonomy for
the Christian and animist people of the south.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Gaddafi tackled the latest developments of the
Mideast peace process and the outcome of Egypt's contacts with the
parties concerned, el-Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
Hopes have increased of reviving the peace process after the
election of moderate Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in May. But
Barak's proposals to delay the implementation of signed peace
agreements have frustrated the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Libyan summit further reviewed the outcome of the
meetings between the two sides on means to boost cooperation in
various domains, el-Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
During Gaddafi's Egyptian visit in March, a number of
agreements were reached on setting up joint ventures in the
fishery industry and on land reclamation. But little has been done
for the implementation.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi crossed into Egypt's border town of Salloum earlier in
the day for the one-day visit. This was his first trip to Egypt
since April when the United Nations Security Council suspended
sanctions after Libya handed over two suspects of blowing up Pan
AM flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988. The explosion
killed 270 people, most of them American or British. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
