<HEADLINE> Iraqi Civilian Killed in U.S.-British Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi civilian was killed
and two others were injured on Wednesday in U.S. and British air
raids on civilian facilities in northern Iraq, an Iraqi military
spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 11:05 local time (0705 GMT), nine
formations of enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace
violated northern Iraqi airspace over the provinces of Dohuk,
Erbil and Neineva, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The warplanes attacked civilian facilities in the region,
causing the casualties, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back and forced the enemy
planes to flee to their base in Turkey, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
At 10:30 (0630 GMT) and 17:27 (1327 GMT), 16 formations of
U.S. and British warplanes coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases
violated southern Iraqi airspace over the provinces of Basra,
Misan, Muthana, Thi-Qar and Qadissiya, he said.
</P>
<P>
They were also forced back to their bases in Saudi Arabia and
Kuwait by Iraqi anti-air forces.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched airstrikes against Iraq
last December, their warplanes which have made more than 10,900
sorties over the northern and southern no-fly zones in Iraq, have
been regularly attacking Iraqi military and civilian targets,
causing severe civilian casualties and property damages.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south against
possible attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
