<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Delegation to Visit Congo Rebel-Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A Zambian delegation led by Eric
Silwamba, Minister in Charge of Presidential Affairs, is expected
in the territories controlled by the rebels of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC), the Rwanda News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is to investigate the leadership wrangle rocking
the main rebel group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD),
rebel sources were quoted as saying. But no exact date was given.
</P>
<P>
There has been dispute within the RCD over who should sign the
Lusaka cease-fire agreement on behalf of the RCD. The six
countries directly involved in the DRC conflict signed the
cease-fire agreement in the Zambian capital on July 10.
</P>
<P>
Reportedly, RCD new leader Emile Illunga backed by Rwanda and
ousted leader Ernest Wamba dia Wamba supported by Uganda, had
contended for the RCD signature.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Jean Pierre Bemba, the leader of the Congolese
Liberation Movement (MLC), also supported by Uganda, signed the
Lusaka peace accord but warned that he may withdraw his signature
if the RCD did not sign within a week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Kigali believe that the current wrangle within the
RCD is rather a reflection of the growing row between Rwanda and
Uganda, major backers of the two rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
Several clashes in Kisangani were reported between the Rwandan
troops stationed there and their Ugandan counterparts, but
officials of both countries continually denied that there was any
friction regarding their policy toward the conflict in the vast
central African country.
</P>
<P>
Disagreement between Rwanda and Uganda over the support to the
rebel movement grew bitter in May this year when after breaching
the regulations of the RCD, Wamba was removed in a special
convention and replaced by Illunga.
</P>
<P>
Illunga reiterated that his movement was still favorable to
signing the Lusaka protocol anytime, once it would have been
agreed that Wamba is just an individual like any other member of
the RCD.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda, and South Africa were also
involved in the mediation, which has so far proven fruitless.
</P>
</TEXT>
