<HEADLINE> Clinton Supports Robertson as New NATO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday expressed his support for British Defense Secretary
George Robertson to be the next secretary-general of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased that our NATO alliance has selected British
Defense Secretary George Robinson to be NATO's next
secretary-general," Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, the 19-member NATO named Robertson as its
secretary-general to replace Javier Solana, who is to become the
European Union foreign policy representative.
</P>
<P>
Robertson is "an extremely talented and dedicated public
servant," Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"He displayed extraordinary leadership during the Kosovo
conflict and has continued to lead in an effort to restore
stability there. I look forward to working with him as he guides
NATO into a new century," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also praised Solana for his contribution to the
alliance, especially during the 78-day air campaign by the allies
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary General Solana has done a superb job steering NATO
through conflict in the Balkans, ushering in three new members to
the alliance, reaching out to the security partners across Europe
and meeting other vital challenges," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
