<HEADLINE> Moderate Newspaper Chief Ordered to Pay Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chief of an Iranian moderate
newspaper was imposed a fine of 23 million rials (about 3,000
U.S. dollars) by a special clerics court's verdict on Wednesday
for "disseminating untruthful and distorted news."
</P>
<P>
The court's verdict, reached after an open trial on July 25,
was handed down on Hojjatoleslam Seyyed Mohammad Khoeiniha,
managing director of the daily "Salam (Hello)".
</P>
<P>
The newspaper was ordered to close down after publishing a
"classified document" of the Intelligence Ministry on July 6.
</P>
<P>
The special clerics court found Khoeiniha "guilty of
disseminating untruthful and distorted news aimed at harming the
public opinion" and sentenced him to a 18-month imprisonment with
lashes according to Islamic Penal Code.
</P>
<P>
The verdict said, however, he has been made to pay the fine
instead due to his background during the pre- and
post-revolutionary period.
</P>
<P>
"And since the accused has also had similar instance of
charges brought against him earlier, he has been suspended
from taking any responsibility as managing director of a press
for a period of three years," the verdict said.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered a ban of the popular newspaper for
five years.
</P>
<P>
Salam reported on July 6 that former Deputy Intelligence
Minister Saeed Emami (also famous as Islami), one of the
main agents behind serial political killings in the country,
has proposed to amend the country's press law in order to
control the press.
</P>
<P>
Emami, who was arrested for masterminding killings of several
Iranian dissidents, committed suicide in prison on June 19 by
taking depilatory substance while taking a bath.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Iran Nation Party Darius Forouhar and his
wife were stabbed to death at home while at least three
dissident writers were mysteriously killed in Tehran later last
year.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the paper, together with a newly-prepared press
law intended to clamp down on the press, led to Tehran University
students' recent protest, in which violent clashes erupted
between students and the police.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that seven students were killed, about 300
injured and 500 arrested in the clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
