<HEADLINE> 80 Pct of Repatriated Tribals Rehabilitated in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 percent of the
repatriated tribals have been rehabilitated properly at their
once-abandoned homes and hearths in Bangladesh's three
southeastern hill districts as per government's 20-point package
of incentives, the national news agency BSS reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The process of rehabilitating internal refugees is at the final
stage, Dipankar Talukdar, chairman of the task force on
repatriated tribals and internal refugees rehabilitation affairs,
was quoted as saying in Rangamati district, 230 km southeast of
Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The non-tribals disturbed by insurgency and displaced
internally would be treated as internal refugees on production of
proper documents, he added.
</P>
<P>
A total of 152,000 families, of which 83,525 are tribals and
68,475 are non-tribals, from the three hill districts of
Rangamati, Khagrachhari and Bandarban have filled the government
supplied forms to be entertained as internal refugees.
</P>
<P>
A total of 64,609 tribals belonging to 12,222 families returned
home in different phases from six refugee camps in the Indian
state of Tripura, bordering the hill district of Khagrachhari.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government signed the Chittagong Hill Tracts
peace agreement on December 2, 1997, with the tribal rebels, which
ended over two decades of armed conflict in the three hill
districts. The repatriation and rehabilitation work started right
after the signing of the accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
