<HEADLINE> Taliban Accuse Opposition of Using Civilians as Human Shields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
Wednesday accused the anti-Taliban northern alliance forces of
using civilians as human shields in the latest fighting in
northern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Taliban admitted that they have shifted
at least 1,800 families in Kapisa and Parwan provinces to the
eastern city of Jalalabad, sources from Kabul told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Kabul, Taliban senior official
responsible for information and culture Mulla Amir Khan Muttaqi
denied the opposition's claim that a large number of people have
been forcibly expelled from northern Afghan provinces by the
Taliban.
</P>
<P>
These families have been shifted due to security reasons as the
opposition was using them as human shields, he said.
</P>
<P>
Muttaqi added that the Taliban have made arrangements to
provide basic facilities to them including foods, water and
medicines.
</P>
<P>
But he denied the opposition's claim about the migration of
250,000 people from the northern areas of the country, saying that
the figure was "much exaggerated."
</P>
<P>
Muttaqi admitted the influx of refugees and displaced Afghans
in Kabul as well, but said they are living with relatives in the
city.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) in Kabul, Christopher Lodhe, said that the Taliban have
informed them of the arrival of a number of displaced persons into
Kabul and asked for help and assistance to them, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC, Lodhe said, is in touch with both the Taliban and the
opposition to provide help and assistance to the displaced Afghans
both in Kabul and the Panjsher valley, the stronghold of
opposition forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
