<HEADLINE> Over 600 Congo Rebels Surrender to SADC Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Spokesman of the Zimbabwean Defense Forces Chancellor Diye said
here on Wednesday that the 617 surrenders were part of a group
that fought against the Zimbabwean National Army (ZNA) at Manono
Village, home village of DRC President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the surrenders follow another surrender of
80 rebels last week at Ankoro, situated along the Congo river.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that since the announcement of the amnesty by Kabila,
the rebels have been waiting for someone to take the lead and with
the situation like this we are expecting to see several thousands
of them responding to the amnesty offer," Diye said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila offered the rebels an olive branch, a week after the
July 10 Lusaka cease-fire agreement, in which was signed by all
the countries involved in the civil war in the Democratic Republic
of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
However, the rebels did not sign because of differences within
their ranks.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said all rebels who had surrendered were now
under the Allied Forces' protection, adding that there were
indications that more rebels were willing to surrender.
</P>
<P>
Since last August, Zimbabwean soldiers together with those from
Angola, Namibia and Chad have been in the DRC assisting Kabila's
embattled government to repel rebels backed by Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
