<HEADLINE> Iran's Basij Kicks off Military Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Basij militiamen, a military
reserve of Iran, began their annual military exercises in the
northeastern part of Tehran Wednesday to mark their role in the
war against Iraq in 1980s.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50,000 Basij militiamen took part in the maneuvers
to initiate the Week of Basij, the official Islamic Republic News
Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Revolution Guards Corps (IRGC) is expected to play
a part in the military exercises by performing acrobatic show,
parachuting and parachute glider show, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
The Basij forces, which are in charge of Iran's internal
security and under the command of the IRGC, were formed by an
order of the late Iranian Supreme leader Ayatollah Khomeini in the
early 1980s during the Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
The Basij volunteers had assisted the Iranian army and the IRGC
during the 1980-88 war by providing logistics, carrying wounded
soldiers, and even directly joining in battles.
</P>
<P>
Local reports alleged the Basij is associated with the
right-wing politicians in the country, hinting that it played a
role in the quenching of university students' call for more press
freedom early last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
