<HEADLINE> S.Lankan Tamil Rebels Agree to Open Supply Route </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka said Wednesday that
Tamil rebels have agreed to open a route for food convoys and
people into rebel-held areas in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
Wednesday sent a message saying that they have agreed to open a
supply route, said Military Spokesman R.P. Witana.
</P>
<P>
The security forces will clear land mines and anti-personnel
mines in the route area and open the route within a few days, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The lack of a supply route to the rebel-held areas have
stranded over 2,000 civilians for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had said more than half a million civilians faced
starvation because the military had closed a route by which relief
supplies were taken to people in the Wanni area under rebel
control.
</P>
<P>
The government has traditionally supplied food and other items
to civilians in rebel-held areas.
</P>
<P>
A route was closed in May when the army launched a fresh
offensive against the LTTE rebels, who have been fighting for a
separate homeland in Sri Lanka's north and east for minority
Tamils since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) launched a
mercy mission last Sunday to evacuate patients in the Wanni area
following reports that four people had died for lack of medicines.
</P>
<P>
During June 29-August 4, the army exchanged as many as 16
letters and messages through the ICRC to the LTTE regarding the
route, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
