<HEADLINE> Syrian Defense Minister Denies Scolding Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Defense Minister General
Mustafa Tlass Wednesday categorically denied his reportedly
insulting remarks about Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Tlass was quoted by local media as saying that "I didn't insult
Arafat personally or used any obscene words against him." He said
that he blasted Arafat's policies of concessions to Israel since
the signing of the Oslo accords in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Tlass was commenting on reports accusing him of insulting
Arafat in a speech delivered on Monday in Lebanon's eastern city
of Baalbec.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Tlass criticized Arafat for "not announcing
Jerusalem a Palestinian capital" and said he "should better not
act as a chicken at the White House and dare say Jerusalem should
be the united capital of the future Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Tuesday urged Syria
to fire Tlass for scorning Arafat, saying "that person (Tlass)
cannot lead the Syrian army" and accused Tlass of having damaged
the fame of the Syrian armed forces and the fraternal ties between
the Syrian and Palestinian peoples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
