<HEADLINE> Iranian FM Calls on Annan to Help End Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has called on U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to help
end the "war and massacre of people in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi made the call during a telephone conversation with
Annan Tuesday night, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
(IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister expressed deep concern over the
continuation of conflicts in the neighboring country and
"intervention of foreign forces" there.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been supporting Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani,
now leader of the opposition forces, while Pakistan backed the
rival Taliban, which controls most of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to IRNA, Rabbani sent Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami, Chairman of the Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC), a letter lately, whose content was not revealed.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban fighters have scored another victory in an
offensive by taking an air base of the opposition forces recently.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi underlined the need to find a diplomatic solution to
the decade-old Afghan civil war instead of resorting to force and
military operations.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed the importance of negotiations between the
belligerent sides and vowed that he would continue his efforts
to cease the military operation in the war-torn country, IRNA
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief further called on Afghanistan's neighbors to
take initiatives in this regard and to exert pressure to end the
bloodshed and presence of foreign forces there.
</P>
<P>
As to the large number of refugees caused by the fightings,
Kharrazi stressed the need to dispatch humanitarian aid to
Afghanistan, a proposal welcomed by Annan, IRNA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
