<HEADLINE> Malaria Vaccination Predicted to Come into Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 4 (xinhua) -- A new and efficacious vaccine
against malaria is expected to be put into use by 2005, an Italian
expert said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Piero Cappuccinelli, professor of Italy's Sassari University,
attending a discussion sponsored by Angola's National Institute of
Public Health, said that the new vaccine is under experiment in
South American countries.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned that the current vaccine against malaria is not
applied extensively for its inefficacy.
</P>
<P>
Malaria, with a terrible nickname "killer of Angolans", claimed
more than 7,500 lives in the southwest African country in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
An official of Angola's health institute said her ministry has
been promoting discussions on epidemics, such as malaria and
sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
Cappuccinelli also considered it is possible for scientists to
develop vaccines against stomach cancer, cocaine abuse and even
pregnancy in 15 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
