<HEADLINE> Six Sentenced to Death in Vietnam's Biggest Corruption Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The People's Court of Ho Chi Minh
Wednesday sentenced six people to death and six others to life
imprisonment for their involvement in Vietnam's biggest ever fraud
and corruption case known as Minh Phung-Epco case, Vietnam News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The death sentences were handed down to the director of Minh
Phung company and vice chairman of the management board of Epco
company, the director of Epco company, a deputy director of Ho Chi
Minh City branch of the Industrial and Commerce Bank of Vietnam, a
deputy director of the Bank for Foreign Trade of Vietnam Ho Chi
Minh City branch, the chairman of the management board of Epco
company and the director of a grain import and export company.
</P>
<P>
Other six business directors or deputy directors were sentenced
to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
All 77 defendants in the case, including 51 business directors
or deputy directors and 18 bank officials, were charged with
defaulting and appropriating public properties worth 5,186 billion
Vietnamese dong (about 350 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Eleven defendants received suspended terms ranging from two to
three years while the rest were sentenced to between three and 20
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
The Minh Phung-Epco case trial, which took investigators more
than two years to complete, lasted for nearly two months from May
10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
