<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges Zimbabwe to Cut State Borrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Wednesday urges
Zimbabwe to cut its domestic borrowing so as to win the bank's 140
million U.S. dollars credit.
</P>
<P>
Resident representative of the World Bank Thomas Allen told
the Zimbabwe News Agency that the plan would involve a
reallocation of budgetary expenditures towards the social sector
and poverty reducing activities.
</P>
<P>
"The strategy can start a virtuous cycle of stabilizing the
currency, lower domestic borrowing costs, lower interest rates,
lower inflation and lower future deficits," Allen said.
</P>
<P>
He said a critical part of the program would be the
acceleration of the government privatization program.
</P>
<P>
The program, he said, aimed to bring in sufficient fiscal
revenues to help reduce the domestic debt to sustainable levels
and relieve the government of costly financial support to
inefficient parastatals.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank was finalizing with the government an
international development agency credit of 140 million U.S.
dollars to be disbursed over a period of six months, providing
budgetary support to the Zimbabwean government.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund Monday approved a 193 million
U.S. dollars standby credit for Zimbabwe to support the nation's
economic reform program over next 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent quarterly disbursements would be made available on
the basis of Zimbabwe's meeting performance targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
