<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on U.N. Presence in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday met in a closed-door session to discuss a report from
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who wants to see a bigger U.N.
presence in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation body heard the briefing by the U.N. special
representative for Sierra Leone, Francis Okelo of Uganda, who is
expected to speak to reporters Wednesday afternoon, a U.N.
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In his written report to the U.N. Security Council late Monday,
Annan recommended increasing a U.N. mission in Sierra Leone to 210
observers from 70 to help implement a recently signed peace accord
between the government and rebels, a U.N. official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A larger U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra Leone (UNOMSIL) would
be needed, depending on a division of labor to be worked out
between the United Nations and a large Nigerian-led West African
force, known as the ECOMOG, that has been supporting the Sierra
Leonean government, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The Peace Agreement, signed on July 7 in Togo's capital of
Lome, requires the UNOMSIL to perform significantly expanded as
well as new tasks in close coordination with the ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the major disarmament and demobilization effort,
implementation of the Lome agreement will require substantial
numbers of peacekeepers throughout the country and the deployment
of additional U.N. military observers, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The number of UNOMSIL military observers would increase to
210," he said, adding that the proposed U.N. mission would be well
above the current strength of about 50 and the authorized strength
of 70.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG's mandate will need to be revised by the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) in consultation with the
United Nations, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Once there is an understanding on the task, strengths and
mandates of the ECOMOG and the U.N. special representative for
Sierra Leone, Annan said, he will submit a more comprehensive
report to the Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0033 </DOCNO>
