<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Asks U.N. to Deal With Destabilizing Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A group of government
experts Wednesday released a report on international efforts to
tackle the destabilizing and excessive accumulation and transfer
of small arms and light weapons now numbering more than 500
million worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The report, produced by a group of more than two dozen experts
from around the world, underscored the fact that while small arms
and light weapons do not cause the conflicts in which they are
used, they do exacerbate and increase their lethality.
</P>
<P>
"Virtually every part of the United Nations system is dealing
in one way or another with the consequences of the armed
conflicts, insecurity, violence, crime, social disruption,
displaced peoples and human suffering that are directly or
indirectly associated with the wide availability of these
weapons," said the 33-page report.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, experts said the insecurity associated with the
wide availability of small arms can undermine efforts to promote
development and post-conflict reconstruction, as well as the
disarmament, demobilization and reintegration of ex-combatants.
</P>
<P>
Among its recommendations, the report called for the
development of practical disarmament measures related to small
arms and light weapons collection in Kosovo, a Serbian province,
given the protracted nature of the crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
The experts also stressed the effect of these weapons on
children, saying that some 300,000 young people under the age of
16 are estimated to have been exploited as participants in the
conflicts using these arms.
</P>
<P>
In response, the report said that the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) and other relevant organizations should focus on the
special needs of affected children in post-conflict situations.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing the important role played by civil society in
efforts to raise awareness of small arms and light weapons, and
its role in proposing solutions, the report called on the United
Nations to further cooperate with non-governmental organizations
towards these ends.
</P>
<P>
An international conference on illicit arms trade in all its
aspects, which the General Assembly has said should be convened in
2001, is also discussed at length in the report.
</P>
<P>
The group of experts was set up under a resolution of the
General Assembly in April 1996 to help the U.N. secretary-general,
Kofi Annan, prepare a report on the types of small arms and light
weapons being used in conflicts being dealt with by the United
Nations, the nature and causes of the excessive and destabilizing
accumulation and transfer of small arms and light weapons,
including their illicit production and trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
