<HEADLINE> 2 Detained Turkish Soldiers to Be Released: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Ambassador to Turkey
Seyed Mohammad Hossain Lavasani said here on Wednesday that Iran
will release the two detained Turkish soldiers in Iran soon.
</P>
<P>
Turkish state-run TRT TV quoted Lavasani as saying that the
two detained Turkish soldiers, who entered the Iranian territory
on July 22, will be freed as quick as possible.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkey told Iran in recent meetings between the two
countries that the continued detention of the two Turkish
soldiers who entered the Iranian territory by mistake was
creating unwanted tension in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"We have assured Iran that the two soldiers entered Iran by
mistake. Turkey does not have a hostile attitude towards Iran,"
said a Turkish senior government official, who asked not to be
named.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we respect Iran's sovereignty and territorial
integrity. It is out of the question for Turkey to violate
Iranian territory."
</P>
<P>
"Neither Iran nor Turkey want tension in ties, but the
continued detention of these two soldiers is creating tension. We
hope that this issue will soon be resolved," added the official.
</P>
<P>
Ties between the two countries were strained when Iran claimed
on July 18 that Turkish warplanes hit an Iranian military post and
tents belonging to Iranian tribesmen.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the bombardment had killed five people
and injured 10 others in the Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has said that the attack was aimed at the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which uses bases in northern Iraq
for hit-and-run attacks on Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has complained that Iran allowed the PKK to move into
Iranian territory after Turkey threatened to use military force to
oust PKK rebels from Syrian territory last fall. But Iran has
denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts between the
Turkish security forces and the PKK militants have claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
