<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Sacks Corruption-Related Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Three officials of Cambodian
Mine Action Center were removed from office Wednesday for being
related to a corruption scandal in the organization which led to
the loss of up to 70,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"On August 2, 1999, Prime Minister Hun Sen made a request for
the appointment of Lt-Gen. Khem Sophoan as Director General of the
Cambodian Mine Action Center (CMAC) in replacement of Sam Sotha,"
a press release issued by CMAC Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen has also signed a sub-decree moving Niem Chouleng from
his position of Assistant Director General to a temporary position
at the Governing Council of the CMAC.
</P>
<P>
Khem Sophoan has resigned from his position of Deputy
Commander-in-Chief of the Royal Cambodian Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
A formal handover of responsibility from Sam Sotha to Khem
Sophoan will take place once the appointment decree has been
signed.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen has also endorsed a decision to temporarily transfer Ek
Bolin from his position of Director of Finance to Assistant
Treasurer.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for the Cambodian government to dismiss
government officials associated with a corruption scandal since
the new government was formed last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the audits, CMAC has mismanaged 50,000 to more
than 70,000 U.S. dollars between 1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
CMAC is a government organization which was set up in 1992 for
the purpose of educating people, training its members and clearing
mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
