<HEADLINE> U.S. Dow Chemical, Union Carbide to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Chemical Co. is buying
Union Carbide Corp. for 9.3 billion U.S. dollars, bolstering Dow
Chemical's position as the world's No. 2 chemical company behind
DuPont, said local press reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The merged company, which will operate under the Dow Chemical
name, will have 24 billion dollars in annual revenues, according
to an Associated Press report from Detroit, Michigan.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 jobs will be cut, leaving about 49,000 employees.
The two companies expect the combination to save 500 million
dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
"This transaction is a giant step in our strategy to transform
Dow into the world's most productive, best `value-growth' company
in the chemical industry," Dow Chemical President and Chief
Executive Officer William S. Stavropoulos was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Union Carbide shareholders will own about 25 percent of Dow
Chemical after the deal is complete, and Union Carbide Chairman
and Chief Executive Officer William Joyce will become vice
chairman of the Dow Chemical board of directors.
</P>
<P>
"This is the right move at a good time," Joyce said in a
statement. "In a consolidating chemical industry where fewer, more
powerful companies will exist, the combination of Dow and Union
Carbide now sets the gold standard for the industry."
</P>
<P>
Union Carbide shareholders will receive 0.537 shares of Dow
Chemical for each of their Union Carbide shares -- or 66.96
dollars based on Tuesday's closing price of Dow Chemical's stock.
The agreement also includes 2.3 billion dollars in assumed debt.
</P>
<P>
The merger depends on the approval of Union Carbide
shareholders and federal regulators. The companies expect it to be
completed by the first quarter of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Dow Chemical, based in Midland, is a leading maker of plastics,
chemicals, hydrocarbons, and herbicides and pesticides. It earned
1.3 billion dollars on revenues of 18.4 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Union Carbide, based in Danbury, Connecticut, produces basic
and specialty chemicals. It had profits of 403 million dollars in
1998 on sales of 5.7 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
