<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Robertson as NATO Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
expressed its support for British Defense Secretary George
Robertson as a candidate for the secretary-general of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In a statement, U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin
welcomed NATO's selection of Robertson Wednesday as the person to
replace Spain's Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
"He is an extremely able minister who has served his government
well, not only during the Kosovo conflict but also in the crucial
debates on NATO's future that preceded the (NATO) Washington
summit," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"He has impressed his alliance colleagues with his knowledge,
leadership abilities and diplomatic skills. These are qualities
which will serve him well as he leads the alliance into the 21st
century," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
If approved, Robertson will take office in early October.
Solana, NATO's current secretary-general, will become the European
Union's foreign policy representative.
</P>
<P>
The approval by the United States, a leading member of the
alliance, is critical for the British secretary to succeed in
becoming chief of the 19-member NATO.
</P>
<P>
Britain has been very supportive in the U.S.-led NATO air
campaign against Yugoslavia. That's a major element for Robertson
to gain support from Washington in his bid for the post.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say Robertson's candidacy could easily be
approved by the members of the alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
