<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Tugrik Rate Down Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Mongolian currency tugrik
continued the downward trend on the foreign exchange market
Wednesday, closing at 1,042 tugrik against the U.S. dollar, or
more than 30 tugrik over the rate in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the slump to government shake-up, political
instability, deepening financial crisis and the inability of some
banks to pay cash to depositors.
</P>
<P>
They also believed that the delayed disbursement of the loan
assistance from donor countries was also partly to blame for the
slip in exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Since the free floating system was introduced in 1993, the
exchange rate of tugrik has constantly declined due to a shortage
of foreign reserves. The recent drop in copper and gold prices on
the international market has led to a sharp fall in the country's
exports, a growing trade deficit and a further shrink of foreign
reserves.
</P>
<P>
Tugrik was traded at 813:1 against the dollar in early 1998 and
fell to 900:1 last November. The government began to intervene
only after the exchange rate broke the psychological barrier of 1,
000:1 on February 21. As a result, the rate was relatively stable
from April to July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Rejects Lee Teng-hui's "Two-States" Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) Wednesday criticized Lee Teng-hui's "two
states" statement, saying that the DPRK supports China's stance on
peaceful reunification of the country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Korean Central News Agency, a Foreign
Ministry spokesman said that his country supports the efforts of
the Chinese Communist Party and government to seek peaceful
reunification of the country under the principle of "one China"
and "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
Lee Teng-hui's definition of the cross-Strait relations as "
state-to-state or at least special state-to-state relations" has
drawn condemnation from all the Chinese people and the countries
the world over, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
