<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO -- A bomb exploded in Northern Province of Sri Lanka
Wednesday noon killing at least 11 people and injuring 21 others,
police said.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said the bombing was the work of the Tamil
rebels.
</P>
<P>
A woman suicide bomber strapped with explosives detonated the
device against the police Special Task Force (STF) truck at
Veppankulam in Vavuniya district, 344 Kilometers from Colombo, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The truck carrying about 30 STF commandos was traveling on the
Vavuniya-Mannar road around noon when the suicide bomber struck.
</P>
<P>
At least 10 police commandos and one civilian were killed and
21 others injured in the blast.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels were blamed for a similar suicide bombing
against a Tamil lawmaker while his car was stuck in a traffic jam
in Colombo last week.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a 16--year-old war against
the government for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of
the country. About 55,000 people have been killed in the war. (
Sri Lanka-Blast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq Wednesday criticized the U.N. Sanctions
Committee for blocking contracts Iraq signed with foreign
companies under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
A total of 457 Iraqi contracts worth 756 million U.S. dollars
signed under the fifth phase of the oil-for-food program are still
blocked by the U.N. Sanctions Committee, said an Iraqi Trade
Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said in a statement carried by the Iraqi
News Agency that Iraq held American and British representatives in
the United Nations committee of responsible for hampering the
endorsement of those contracts.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the continuation of hampering the contracts
revealed the aggressive policy pursued by the United States and
Britain toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that those contracts comprise 95 for the industrial
sector and 72 for the health sector while the other contracts
cover the sectors of transport, oil, commerce, water and sewage,
irrigation, higher education and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is allowed to export limited
amount of oil in every six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the deal, the ceiling of the amount
of oil Iraq is allowed to export has been raised to 5.2 billion
dollars from 2 billion dollars for the first three phases. (Iraq-
UN-Contracts)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli soldiers sealed off a divided Hebron in
West Bank Wednesday after two Jewish settlers were wounded in an
ambush possibly carried out by Palestinian militants overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli soldiers imposed a curfew on the Israeli-controlled
part of the city and set up roadblocks around the city, barring
Palestinians from entering and leaving the city.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers also carried out home searches and questioned
people.
</P>
<P>
Two settlers were lightly wounded when unidentified gunmen
opened fire on them Tuesday night while they were driving through
the downtown on the way home in the Jewish settlement of Tel
Romeida in the heart of a Palestinian neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
The shooting was the first incident of its kind since Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak took office early last month.
</P>
<P>
Barak has warned of such terror attacks as the troubled Israeli-
Palestinian peace process moves forward. (Hebron-Shooting)
</P>
</TEXT>
