<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Pakistan Halved by Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in Pakistan
slumped by 51 percent in 1998-99 due to the economic sanctions
imposed by the Western countries after its nuclear tests,
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of foreign investment declined to 403 million U.S.
dollars during the 1998-99 fiscal year from 822 million dollars in
the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Direct foreign investment plunged 37 percent to 376 million
dollars while portfolio investment fell 67 percent to a mere 27
million dollars, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain and Japan remain the leading
investors in Pakistan despite their sanctions against the country
following its nuclear tests in May last year.
</P>
<P>
But Western countries' sanctions inhibited international
financial institutions like the International Monetary Fund and
the World Bank from providing fresh major loans to the South Asian
country.
</P>
<P>
The economic difficulties resulting from lacking of foreign aid
also kept the portfolio investors from the stock markets in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The power sector received 131 million dollars as the biggest
beneficiary, followed by mining with 69 million dollars and
chemical, pharmaceutical and fertilizers with 54 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
