<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New NATO Chief Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Minister George
Robertson was formally appointed Wednesday as the new chief of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
During a regular meeting, NATO members' 19 representatives
approved the appointment of Robertson as successor to Spain's
Javier Solana, the outgoing NATO secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
Solana said in a statement after the appointment that he had
worked closely with Robertson over the last two years and "have
valued his support and advice on all the key issues facing the
Alliance."
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to working with him closely in my new capacity
as High Representative of the European Union for the Common
Foreign and Security Policy and to our joint efforts to build a
stronger European role and responsibility in NATO," said Solana,
who will step down in October.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair last Friday proposed
Britain's NATO chief candidacy of the 53-year-old Robertson.
</P>
</TEXT>
