<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Rand Recovery Stabilizes Money Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The South African rand
recovered on Wednesday from its sell-off earlier in the week,
serving as a stabilizer to the money market rates.
</P>
<P>
The rand gained some 8 cents against the U.S. dollar and was
traded at 6. 1380 rand per dollar from Tuesday's worst level of
6.2220 rand per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the recovery, the repo rate (central bank prime
lending rate) dipped to 13.620 percent Wednesday from 13.630
percent on Monday and Tuesday, as commercial banks under-bid for
the 12.9 billion rand (6.1 billion dollars) repos on offer after
the South African Reserve Bank (SARB) matched the estimated
liquidity requirement.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks only bid 12.435 billion rand (6 billion
dollars) for the 12.9 billion rand worth of repos on offer.
</P>
<P>
Since the liquidity requirement rose above 11 billion rand (1.8
billion dollars) on July 13 under-bidding has been frequent as the
commercial banks have run out of the collateral assets needed to
put in a bid for the SARB's repos.
</P>
<P>
Market sources said the recovery in the rand has eased jitters
that interest rates were headed higher, although they did rise
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"There are market jitters ahead of (former labour minister
Tito) Mboweni' s inauguration on Saturday, but I think they are
overdone. That is part of the reason why the rand recovered
today," one money market dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni will be inaugurated as SARB governor on August 7, after
current governor Chris Stals retires after 44 years with the SARB,
of which the last 10 years was as governor.
</P>
<P>
The first trading day after Mboweni's inauguration is August
10, as August 9 is a public holiday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
