<HEADLINE> Factfile of Newly-elected ITTF President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Adham
Sharara was elected as President of the International Table Tennis
Federation (ITTF) in the ITTF General Assembly here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following is factfile:
</P>
<P>
Sharara started playing table tennis as a young boy in Cairo,
Egypt, and immigrated to Canada in 1967, when he was still a
teenager.
</P>
<P>
He continued to improve his skills at the Chateauguay
Club, on the outskirts of Montreal. There, he began to coach young
players inlucding Mariann Domonkos, who became a 10-time Canadian
women champion. His early intention was to become a professional
electrical engineer, but soon changed his mind and decided to become
a good table tennis player.
</P>
<P>
In 1974 Sharara was a member of the Canadian contingent that
trained in Japan. Then he leaned from a famous European coach, Zlatko
Condas, how to improve several skills. When Zlatko left Canada in 1977,
Sharara had the opportunity to coach the Canadian teams at
international competitions including the Commonwealth and world
championships.
</P>
<P>
Sharara became the Technical Director for the Canadian Table
Tennis Association and in short time was promoted to the CEO
position. Up to this time his efforts and contributions were as a
volunteer. He re-organized the association with a masterplan and
developed a strategy to accelerate the functions of the
administrators and the technicians alike. He became a director for
the Canadian Olympic Association.
</P>
<P>
In 1988 Sharara was nominated to be the North American Council
member for the ITTF and seven years later he moved from Vice President
to Deputy President. He was elected as ITTF President in
one-candidate voting on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. May Buy Back National Debt for 1st Time Since 1972 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
said Wednesday that it is exploring buying back a portion of the
3.6 trillion dollar national debt held by the public.
</P>
<P>
In seeking ways to manage the government's finances in a new
era of budget surpluses, the Treasury Department released for
public comment a proposal that would allow it to take competitive
offers from bond holders on a voluntary basis to reduce the amount
of debt. The department said that after a 60-day comment period
they hope to establish final rules for the procedure by January.
</P>
<P>
"It is critically important that we manage the debt held by the
public as efficiently as we can in this new environment," Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The department has not bought back securities since 1972, when
a few existing bonds and notes held by the public were swapped for
new debt issues.
</P>
<P>
Because of huge budget deficits in the 1980s and early 1990s,
the national debt has exploded, climbing from less than 1 trillion
dollars to 5.5 trillion dollars currently.
</P>
<P>
Of that amount, 3.6 trillion dollars are in public hands and
the rest is held by government trust funds, the largest one being
the Social Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration last year enjoyed its first budget
surplus since 1969. And the administration and the Congressional
Budget Office are projecting continued surpluses over the next 15
years, assuming agreements to cut government spending are honored,
enough to totally eliminate the 3.6 trillion dollars in debt held
by the public in 2015.
</P>
<P>
This prospect is requiring the Treasury to explore ways to
better manage the massive Treasury securities market.
</P>
<P>
Up until now, it has been able to just reduce the size of new
borrowings rather than being required to buy back debt from the
public. But officials said they do not want to reduce current
offerings too much and believe they can save taxpayers money
through lower interest rates by buying back debt already held by
the public, much of it at higher rates than current offerings
received.
</P>
<P>
Summers told reporters that use of debt buybacks raises a
"number of complex issues that will need to be worked out."
</P>
<P>
Officials stressed that any government purchases would be on an
entirely voluntary basis. They would be done through a type of
reverse auction in which the government would announce the type of
securities it was interested in buying and accept the most
competitive bids from holders of those securities.
</P>
<P>
If bond holders wanted too much to sell their securities back
to the government, the Treasury would have the option of making no
purchases for that option. 
</P>
</TEXT>
