<HEADLINE> Allied Forces to Retaliate Upon Congolese Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The allied forces fighting
alongside the Congolese troops Wednesday said they will retaliate
in self defense against rebels defying the cease-fire agreement
signed in Lusaka last month.
</P>
<P>
Spokesperson of the Zimbabwean Defense Ministry Alphios
Makotore Wednesday said in a statement that while the regional and
the international community were busy making diplomatic manoeuvres
to end the year-old war in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC), rebels and their allies seemed to have their own plans.
</P>
<P>
"On August 2, the rebels and their allies attacked allied force
positions with both small and heavy arms fire in the areas of
Munenge, Lubenga and Dibenge," Makotore said.
</P>
<P>
He said the allied forces comprising Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola
and Chad remain committed to the cease-fire agreement signed in
Lusaka on July 10.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda are supporting the rebels who since August 2
last year had been fighting to topple DRC President Laurent
Kabila's government. 
</P>
