<HEADLINE> Germany To Keep Ban On British Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany is to keep the ban on
British beef despite the recent lifting of the worldwide ban.
</P>
<P>
British beef was banned globally in 1996 over fears of mad cow
disease. The 15-nation European Union, of which Germany is a
member, last month authorized exports to resume from August 1.
</P>
<P>
However, Germany's health minister Andrea Fischer told BBC
Radio 4's Today program that the German authorities wanted to make
sure that the UK's beef industry checks were working properly.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is also maybe in British interests that we take
some more measures of reinforcing trust in Germany in British
beef," said the German minister, a member of the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment I think the German market is quite difficult for
British beef because people maybe would not want to buy it," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The decision -- only 48 hours after the EU's global export ban
was lifted -- shocked British farmers and provoked a frenzy of
activity in the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Elliot Morley told BBC, "If Germany is
going to unduly delay lifting the ban, then there is no doubt that
the Commission has the power to take legal action against Germany
and they have indicated they will do so."
</P>
<P>
National Farmers' Union deputy president Tim Bennett said,
"Quite frankly we are angry and exasperated by this delay. All we
are asking for is that the German consumer has the choice."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
