<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Agencies Prepared to Tackle Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Government agencies and state
enterprises in Thailand have made progress in tackling the Year
2000 problem, or Y2K, Minister of Science, Technology and
Environment Arthit Urairat said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There are nothing to be worried about as government agencies
and state enterprises had been making good progress in solving the
problem, the minister was quoted by the Thai News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem, or the millennium bug, is expected to hit
computers that still use two digits to represent years. There are
fears that once the year 2000 arrives, computers could mistake it
for 1900, thus causing them to produce flawed data or crash.
</P>
<P>
According to Arthit, some state enterprises, particularly those
in the energy sector, were now said to be 100 percent ready for
the bug.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned the Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand
and the Petroleum Authority of Thailand among others.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister Trairong Suwannakhiri has
ordered all government agencies to submit their reports on
progress in preparation for the Y2K problem within 15 days.
</P>
<P>
The National Electronics and Computer Technology Center has
also urged private firms, especially small and medium-sized ones,
to pay more attention to the bug problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
