<HEADLINE> Namibia Declares State of Emergency in Caprivi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) --Namibian President Sam Nujoma
declared Wednesday a formal state of emergency in the strife-torn
Caprivi Region in north-eastern Namibia following clashes between
government troops and secessionists.
</P>
<P>
Caprivi's secessionist attacked government facilities Monday
and triggered off confrontations with government troops, which
caused 13 casualties.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a statement that under state of
emergency, the security force were authorized to interrogate any
person and enter any place, search any person or place and seize
any property which could be used, among others, as evidence in
criminal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian government had reportedly called on Denmark to
revoke the refugee status of Caprivi separatist leader Mishake
Muyongo and "treat him as the leader of a terrorist group".
</P>
<P>
The government accused Muyongo, who was granted asylum in
Denmark in May, of having "fled the country in order to engage in
insurrection".
</P>
<P>
According to other report, Namibian refugees at the Dukwe
refugee camp in Botswana Tuesday staged celebratory dances for the
possible suspension of their repatriation after watching fighting
between Namibian security operatives and Caprivi secessionist
rebels on television. 
</P>
