<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Hard Hit by Shortage of Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Only one in 30 new entrants
into South Africa's labor market would find jobs in the formal
sector of the economy, the Human Sciences Research Council (HSRC)
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said estimations showed that 72 percent of the unemployed
were under the age of 40, and 40 percent of people older than 20
were illiterate or severely under-educated.
</P>
<P>
The study found that 30 percent of the people interviewed said
they could not get employment due to a lack of education, low
skills and inadequate work experience.
</P>
<P>
These figures were revealed in an HSRC study conducted between
October last year and January this year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15 percent were aware of job creation programs, but
95 percent of the respondents were eager to participate in such
projects.
</P>
<P>
The research council said that more than half of the people
asked were willing to participate in job creation initiatives
unconditionally, while 21 percent of the respondents would first
want to know the conditions of employment.
</P>
<P>
It said 47 percent of those reluctant to participate in job
creation projects cited problems on the way the programs were
being managed, such as nepotism and not receiving wages for work
done.
</P>
<P>
About 28 percent of the respondents said a shortage of job
opportunities where they lived and too many people looking for
work constituted the main obstacles in finding a job.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,000 people were interviewed in the three
provinces with the highest incidents of unemployment -- the
Eastern Cape, Northern Province and KwaZulu-Natal -- and the three
provinces with the lowest incidents of joblessness, the Free
State, Gauteng and Western Cape.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that 90 percent of the respondents were
prepared to take any job, and 84 percent of those interviewed
reported that they were actively looking for work.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that 46 percent of the women interviewed in
rural areas had worked before, compared with 54 percent of the men
in those areas. In urban regions, 61 percent of women had
previously been employed, compared with 68 percent of the men.
</P>
</TEXT>
