<HEADLINE> U.S., Israel to Invest More Money for Laser Weapon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Israel
will put more money to continue development of the Tactical High
Energy Laser weapon fur use against short-range projectiles like
the Katyusha rockets, the U.S. Army Space and Missile Defense
Command said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gerda Sherrill, a spokesman for the command, said the program
has cost $130.8 million since it started in 1996. It ran into
problems with schedule delays and cost overruns that forced a
choice between halting the project or investing more.
</P>
<P>
TRW Space and Electronics Group of Redondo Beach, Calif, the
contractor for the Tactical High Energy Laser weapon, has
threatened to quit the project last spring unlest the government
put more money into it.
</P>
<P>
The contract was modified in June. And according to the
modified contract, TRW will pay half of the additional development
cost until it successfully shoots down a Katyusha rocket in flight
during field testing at White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico,
while the U.S. and Israeli governments will pay the other half,
amounting to $46.6 million.
</P>
<P>
After a successful shootdown, TRW will pay one-quarter of the
remaining costs and the two governments will pay the rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
