<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassies Still Vulnerable to Bomb Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Four out of five U.S.
embassies and consulates around the world are still vulnerable to
bomb attacks similar to those that blast embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania a year ago, because of their unadequate protective
measures, officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Kennedy, assistant secretary of state for
administration, said an assessment by a government commission
found that fewer than 50 of the 265 U.S. diplomatic outposts
meet the standard of a safety perimeter that would protect them
from large car bombs.
</P>
<P>
Last August, the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania were
destroyed by car bombs, killing 226 people, including 12
Americans.
</P>
<P>
As the threat of a repeat attack continue, nearly 70
embassies had been closed for one day or more because of safety
concerns or specific threats since the bombings, said Peter
Bergin, deputy secretary of state for diplomatic security.
</P>
<P>
He said 4,000 new local security guards had been hired,
streets closed, perimeter property purchased and
counter-terrorism equipment installed at posts around the world
since the bombings.
</P>
<P>
"In our view, we've improved diplomatic security worldwide,
but there's more we will do," Bergin told a briefing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
