<HEADLINE> Russia's Luzhkov, Regional Leaders Form Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Russia's leading regional leaders
and Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov on Wednesday forged an alliance
aiming at winning the upcoming parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony in Moscow, Luzhkov signed papers forming a
coalition between his Fatherland party and the All Russia group of
regional leaders including the president of Russia's Tatarstan
region, Mintimer Shaimiyev.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to gaining a constructive majority in the
State Duma which will later allow the president to form his
cabinet on the basis of a parliamentary majority,'' Shaimiyev told
a news conference. The parliamentary race is scheduled for
December this year.
</P>
<P>
"This is the only way to eradicate the main cause of conflicts
between the branches of power," Shaimiyev said, in an apparent
reference to Russia's political landscape that saw four prime
ministers in the last year and a half and confrontation between
President Boris Yeltsin and the State Duma lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov, widely believed to harbor presidential ambitions, said
the new group would seek to recruit former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov. Primakov, 69, won praise during his nine-months as
premier for establishing political stability after Russia's August
1998 financial crisis. He was dismissed by Yeltsin last May.
</P>
<P>
"We have all known Yevgeny (Primakov) for a long time and
deeply respect him,'' the mayor said. "The political council of
the Fatherland movement is ready to put his candidacy at number
one in the national list of candidates for the State Duma.''
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov, a critic of the way economic reforms have been carried
out by Russia's changing governments, has said he could run for
president if he saw no other suitable candidate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
