<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-04 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Deputy Minister Mastermind of Serial Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's former deputy intelligence
minister Saeed Emani was the mastermind of the serial murder of
Iranian dissidents last year, the judicial organization of the
country's armed forces concluded on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The judicial organization released for the first time a picture
of Emani, known as Eslami, who committed suicide in prison on June
19 by taking depilatory substance while taking a bath.
</P>
<P>
Emani is blamed for the mysterious deaths of leader of the Iran
Nation Party Darius Forouhar and his wife, and at least three
dissident writers in Tehran later last fall.
</P>
<P>
In a lengthy statement carried by the official Islamic Republic
News Agency (IRNA), the judicial organization said all principals
and internal agents involved in the murder have been identified.
</P>
<P>
The statement was produced on the basis of an all-out
investigation by "a group of highly specialized security
officers" under the supervision of Tehran's military court to
"identify the root cause" of the serial killings.
</P>
<P>
The investigation is still going on.
</P>
<P>
The statement detailed the design, plotting and execution of
the serial killings, and branded those agents involved as
attempting to "create crisis and insecurity in the society."
</P>
<P>
It said that five months prior to the first murder, the agents
embarked on identification of their subjects.
</P>
<P>
Documents available showed that in addition to those murdered,
other persons were also targeted for future operations.
</P>
<P>
The agents first planned a mass killing through bombing or
firing by a machine-gun at a gathering, but later changed their
mind and murdered their subjects individually in a cruel and
atrocious manner to provoke people's sentiments, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Forouhar and his wife were stabbed to death in their home.
</P>
<P>
Emami, after being arrested, admitted involvement in the
murder.
</P>
<P>
Another key agent accused said another motive behind the murder
was to provoke human rights agencies to demand permission to visit
Iran which would have been rejected and consequently Iran would
have been isolated in the international scene.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said the agents had tried to wage a
mental war to blame either the Islamic Revolution Guards Corps
or the intelligence minister for the killings.
</P>
<P>
It said that 23 people were prosecuted, but a number of them
proved to have played no role in the murder were released on bail.
</P>
<P>
After six months, the inquiry showed that the Islamic system
had suffered great damage and irreparable blow, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that all information related to the case
would be offered to the public at a suitable time and that
all the data presented are based on legal documents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
