<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's UNITA Implicated in Namibian Unrest: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) is being implicated in
the rebel violence in the Caprivi Strip in northeastern Namibia,
South Africa's SABC television reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that 50 of the rebels, who Monday attacked
Namibian security forces in Katima Mulilo in the Caprivi, entered
Namibia from Angola, said SABC television.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, believed to belong to secessionist Caprivi
Liberation Army, launched an attack on the Katima Mulilo police
station, the nearby airport and occupied the offices of the
state-owned Namibian Broadcasting Corporation radio station.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were later suppressed by government forces. Fifteen
people were believed to have been killed in skirmishes.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leader Mishake Muyongo, who is now in exile in Denmark,
said pressure on the Namibian government to give Caprivi greater
autonomy failed, forcing his men to take up arms.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the SABC television Tuesday, he said
Caprivi has never been part of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Muyongo, who was former leader of Namibia's major opposition
Democratic Turnhalle Alliance, fled to neighboring Botswana last
October, days before the Namibian government claimed to have
uncovered a secessionist plot in the Caprivi. More than 100 armed
men followed him.
</P>
<P>
Muyongo was granted asylum by the Botswanan authorities in
February this year and was later resettled in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The SABC said calm returned to Katima Mulilo Wednesday with
curfew lifted and roadblocks removed and people going about their
regular business. Most government offices and businesses reopened.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Namibian government has called on Denmark to
revoke Muyongo's refugee status and treat him as a terrorist
leader, according to the SABC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
