<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Hails Annan's Report on Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday extended a welcome to a report by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, saying that the 15-nation body will "provide active
support" to the peace agreement, which ended conflicts in the
Western African country of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
Security Council, Martin Andjaba of Namibia, said, "Members of
the Council expressed their determination to provide active
support to the Lome Peace Agreement," which was signed in July
in Togo.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Council met in a closed-door
session to discuss a report from Annan, who wants to see a bigger
U.N. presence in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation body heard the briefing by the U.N. special
representative for Sierra Leone, Francis Okelo of Uganda. The
Council president described the briefing as useful.
</P>
<P>
In his written report to the U.N. Security Council late Monday,
Annan recommended increasing a U.N. mission in Sierra Leone to 210
observers from 70 to help implement a recently signed peace accord
between the government and rebels.
</P>
<P>
A larger U.N. Observer Mission in Sierra Leone (UNOMSIL) would
be needed, depending on a division of labor to be worked out
between the United Nations and a large Nigerian-led West African
force, known as ECOMOG, that has been supporting the Sierra
Leonean Government, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the major disarmament and demobilization effort,
implementation of the Lome agreement will require substantial
numbers of peacekeepers throughout the country and the deployment
of additional U.N. military observers, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The number of UNOMSIL military observers would increase to
210," he said, adding the proposed U.N. mission would be well
above the current strength of about 50 and the authorized strength
of 70.
</P>
<P>
Once there is an understanding on the task, strengths and
mandates of ECOMOG and the U.N. special representative for Sierra
Leone, Annan said he will submit a more comprehensive report to
the Security Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
