<HEADLINE> SADC FMs Discuss Lesotho Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from four
Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries are in
Lesotho to speed up the resolution of the country's political
problems, South African radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The four foreign ministers are from South Africa, Zimbabwe,
Mozambique and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho has still to hold elections since the unrest that led
to a SADC military intervention last year.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,500 South African and Botswana troops crossed into
Lesotho in September last year at the request of Lesotho Prime
Minister Pakalitha Mosisili, in a bid to restore peace and
stability after a mutiny in the Lesotho Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
The unrest followed allegations by the country's three major
opposition parties that the general election on May 23, 1998 had
been rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy,
which won 79 of 80 seats in parliament. 
</P>
