<HEADLINE> World Bank Pledges Aid to Nigerian Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian presidential statement
said Wednesday that the World Bank has pledged to support the
country's economic restructuring programs.
</P>
<P>
James Wolfensohn, President of the World Bank, was quoted as
saying in his letter to Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo that
he was encouraged by the anti-corruption stance of Obasanjo and
ready to provide more help to the country's economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said that all new World Bank financial assistance to
Nigeria would attract concessional interest rates of 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Payment of the principal will be over 35 years after an initial
10-year grace period and the terms will apply until Nigeria's
external financial position shows significant improvement, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has already offered
Nigeria a one- billion-U.S. dollar loan to help revive the economy
of the most populous African nation, dependent on agreement of a
stand-by arrangement to last a minimum of six months and maximum
of 12 months. 
</P>
