<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Tanzanian Public Firms Sold to Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian has sold 260
public firms to foreigners and 40 to domestic businessmen in the
privatization process, Minister of State in the President's
Office, Nassoro Malocho, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the National Assembly in central city of
Dodoma that the trend has shown that Tanzanians have insufficient
economic power to buy the parastatal institutions.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Malocho said Tanzanians
have made many bids for the purchase of parastatal enterprises
under the Presidential Parastatal Service Reform Commission, but
they often have difficulties in concluding the sales because they
don't have enough money.
</P>
<P>
Although the government is happy to see Tanzanians buy the
ailing public corporations, it is difficult to come to their
assistance, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the minister said that last year Tanzania sold 29
public firms, earning 57.38 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government had planned to divest 50 firms last year, but
sales agreement were concluded for only 29, Malocho said, adding
that the government will continue to divest the state-owned firms
through the reform commission at a rate of 50 a year.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that many firms are in the red, unable to pay
salaries to employees and have huge liabilities, which scares away
investors.
</P>
<P>
By last December, 270 out of 395 public firms scheduled for
divestiture had been sold and the remaining 125 were at different
stages of privatization.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to divest parastatal companies to create
more jobs and enhance national income.
</P>
<P>
The firms cover telecommunications, harbors, water and
sanitation, as well as petroleum refinery and railway sectors.
</P>
<P>
The government has agreed with World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund to remove 50 companies from government control
annually.
</P>
<P>
Between July 1997 and June 1998, a total of 52 companies and
nine non- core entities were divested, according to the figures
released by the Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
