<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Japan's Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Clinton said
Wednesday that the trends of Japan's economy are positive as it
recovers from its longest recession since World War II.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton also said he was not concerned about currency
fluctuations in Japan.
</P>
<P>
"In the last six and a half years, we've seen the currency
fluctuations _ they go up, they go down. I don't have anything to
comment about that," he said when answering questions during a
brief appearance after meeting his economic team at the white
house.
</P>
<P>
"I think that we do see some signs that Japan's economy is
beginning to grow and that Prime Minister Obuchi has formed a
coherent and strong and effective government, and has secured the
necessary support from the Japanese people to continue to move
forward," he told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
"So we will continue to consult with Japan about what we think
is important for their economic recovery, as we should, because
they're our partners and they're our friends and our allies and
their recovery is critical to Asia's recovery," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, who marked his first year in office last Friday, has
succeeded in pushing through a massive bank bailout and speeding
up the pace of reforms in the nation's moribund financial system.
</P>
<P>
But the ultimate measure of his administration -- whether he
can restore economic growth -- remains unclear, with recent
indicators giving conflicting signs.
</P>
<P>
On the U.S. economy, Clinton attributed the sustained expansion
to his "new economic strategy founded on fiscal discipline,
investment in our people and expanded trade".
</P>
<P>
"America has come a long way in the last seven years; from
recession to recovery, from economic disorder to a fiscal house
finally in order," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
