<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Finishes Lineup of Expanding Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak finished the expansion of his cabinet Thursday by appointing
five new ministers from left and center coalition parties.
</P>
<P>
The 120-member Knesset, or parliament, approved the
appointments of the new ministers and eight deputy ministers by a
vote of 52-16 with eight abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Barak appointed Professor Yuli Tamir, a founder of the Peace
Now movement, as minister of immigration and absorption, making
her the second woman in the cabinet. As a Labor party member,
Tamir failed to reach a realistic spot on the party's Knesset
list in its primaries before the May election.
</P>
<P>
Former army chief of staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak of the Center
Party was appointed tourism minister. And former deputy chief of
staff Matan Vilnai, who joined the Labor Party before the
election, was named as minister of science, culture and sports.
</P>
<P>
Haim Oron of the left-wing Meretz party was named agriculture
minister. And Rabbi Michael Malchior, a member of the moderate
religious party Meimad, which formed an alliance with the Labor
party ahead of the election, was named minister in the Prime
Minister's Office for diaspora affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ousting right-wing Benjamin Netanyahu in the prime ministerial
race, Barak has managed to cobble together a coalition of seven
parties controlling 75 seats in the 15-faction Knesset, the
widest parliamentary majority in Israel in years.
</P>
<P>
He has sought to expand his 18-member cabinet, which took
office early last month, to accommodate demands of coalition
partners vying for governmental positions.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset last week approved a bill presented by the
coalition, allowing the sitting prime minister to decide the size
of his cabinet. The maximum number of cabinet ministers was 18
under the previous law.
</P>
<P>
Barak also named Arab Israeli Knesset member Nawaf Massalha of
the Labor Party as deputy foreign minister. This is the highest
position ever held by an Arab Israeli in the government.
</P>
<P>
Arabs account for 18 percent of the Israeli population, which
is about 6 million, but they have felt discriminated in every
field. Barak has been criticized for failing to break a long-time
taboo which excludes Arab Israeli from the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet expansion has spurred criticism both in the
coalition and in the opposition bloc. Critics have blamed Barak
for wasting millions of public funds in order to pay off his
coalition partners for their support in the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
