<HEADLINE> Iran Threatens Power Against Taliban Over Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran threatened here on Thursday
to act with power if the Taliban fails to identify and punish the
killers of its diplomats and correspondent in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We will not rest until we get a satisfactory answer," Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said while speaking to the
victims' families on the first anniversary of their deaths.
</P>
<P>
Eight Iranian diplomats and a correspondent of the official
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) were killed a year ago when
the Taliban troops took over Mazar-e-Sharif, a strategic town in
northern Afghanistan, from opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi insisted that Iran's demand of identifying and
punishing the perpetrators of the massacre should be met.
</P>
<P>
Iran was outraged by the killings last year and massed nearly
200,000 troops along the border to put pressure on Taliban, which
brought most of Afghanistan under control in the fighting with its
opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
The massing of troops "was a show of power and if the Taliban
fails to heed our demands, then we will act with power and will
force them to abide by our demands." Kharrazi was quoted by IRNA
as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that through combined efforts, including international
pressure, diplomatic prowess, and display of military might on
the border, Iran had succeeded in forcing the Taliban to return
the bodies of the killed and free other Iranians who were
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
These "were great accomplishments," Kharrazi said, adding
Iran's handling of its relations with Afghanistan was prudent and
wise.
</P>
<P>
He said Iran should follow the developments in the neighboring
country carefully and stay vigilant in defending its own national
interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
