<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Jobless Claims Rise Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said
Thursday that the number of new claims for unemployment benefits
edged up last week after hitting their lowest level in two years
the week before.
</P>
<P>
According to the Department's report, 279,000 people filed new
claims for jobless benefits for the week ending July 31, up by
4,000 from the previous week. Last week's level was the highest
since July 17 when claims were at 315,000.
</P>
<P>
The four-week moving average for claims, which smoothes out
week-to-week volatility, was down a little to 295,000 last week.
That was the lowest level since March 27 when claims were at
293,750.
</P>
<P>
Last week's increase was slightly less than some economists
expected but still kept claims at a level indicating the nation's
job market remains healthy.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department said Thursday that for the week ending
July 24, six states and territories reported increases in jobless
claims, while 47 had decreases. The state data lag a week behind
the national figures.
</P>
<P>
The state with the biggest increase in applications for jobless
benefits was Ohio, up 6,286, while Michigan recorded the biggest
decrease, 22,777, which was attributed to fewer layoffs in the
automobile industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
