<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economy to Grow 2-3 Percent: Lehman Brothers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Thai economy is likely to
grow between two and three percent this year before jumping to 5.5
percent next year, Thai News Agency quoted the leading U.S.
investment bank Lehman Brothers as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lehman's projection exceeds that of the Thai government's
growth target of one percent for this year, after the economy
suffered an eight percent contraction last year.
</P>
<P>
Jasjit Bhattal, Lehman Brothers' new chairman for the Asia
Pacific region, said that the improved outlook of the Thai economy
was a result of the government's expansionary fiscal policy and
low interest rates that boosted domestic consumption and consumer
confidence.
</P>
<P>
An Increase in manufacturing production, which the company
forecast at 10-20 percent of growth this year, a rise in share
prices and stronger exports also supported the country's economic
recovery, he said.
</P>
<P>
The renowned investment bank also projected that the Thai baht
would strengthen to 33 against the U.S. dollar by the end of this
year while the stock market will continue to rise as a reflection
of the positive trends of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The company forecast Thailand's inflation this year will be
minus one percent before it moves higher to positive one percent
next year.
</P>
<P>
Bhattal also praised the Thai government for its success in
reducing short-term external debts and in acquiring continual
capital inflows.
</P>
<P>
He said that although non-performing loans in Thailand's
banking sector stood at about 50 percent it was no surprise to
investors.
</P>
<P>
However, he suggested that the Thai government continue efforts
to reform the country's banking system to reduce problem loans,
thereby encouraging banks to resume lending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
