<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Malaysia to Promote All-Round Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Malaysia are
expected to agree on further bilateral cooperation in trade,
investment, tourism and joint border development on the Eighth
Thailand-Malaysia Joint Commission to be officially inaugurated
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
A plenary meeting of senior officials of the two neighbors was
opened here Thursday, which served as a prelude to the meeting
between Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan and his Malaysian
counterpart Dato Seri Syed Hamid Albar Friday.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the Thai Foreign Ministry said that
bilateral relations between the two countries are now at an
excellent level, as close ties and cooperation at all levels have
been pursued for years with exchange of visits by the two
countries' leaders and senior officials.
</P>
<P>
The joint commission is expected to come to an agreement on
facilitating entrepreneurs, business people and tourists from both
countries to visit each other's country with greater convenience.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1987, the Thailand-Malaysia Joint Commission is the
first of its kind that Thailand has established with other
countries.
</P>
<P>
It aims to promote bilateral cooperation in the fields of
politics, economics, security, transportation, communication,
public health, education and science and technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
