<HEADLINE> Communications Circles Denounce Lee's Splittist Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- China's communications circles
today denounced Lee Teng-hui's "two-states" statement, accusing
him of placing new obstacles in the way of the "three exchanges"
across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Communications Huang Zhendong told a seminar that
Lee's splittist remarks have severely damaged the relations
between the two sides of the straits, and once again undermined
endeavors to push forward cross-strait exchanges of direct mail,
trade, and air and shipping services.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the direct shipping service between Xiamen and
Fuzhou ports in Fujian Province and Kaohsiung Port in Taiwan since
1997 has been widely welcomed by trade, shipping and other
business circles on both sides of the straits.
</P>
<P>
The direct shipping service has not only boosted cross-straits
container shipment, but also benefited the development of
Kaohsiung Port, which is now the third-largest container port in
the world, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
"A steady development of cross-straits relations and the 'three
exchanges' is in keeping with the fundamental interests of the
people on both sides," Huang added. "Under the principle of 'one
China', the Ministry of Communications is prepared to make
unceasing contributions to the development of the 'three exchanges
' and the peaceful reunification of China."  
</P>
</TEXT>
