<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Introduce Tele-Medicine by 2000: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia will introduce
tele-medicine (computer link treatment) by the year 2000, a
professor said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a two-day national workshop, Legesse Zerihun,
associate dean of the Addis Ababa University Faculty of Medicine,
said that Ethiopia had been selected to serve as a tele-medicine
center for East African sub- region.
</P>
<P>
Following the introduction of computer technology, Ethiopians
living in remote areas would be able to get medical consultancy
services from health centers in towns through a software link,
Legesse predicted.
</P>
<P>
He said the technology would enable health professionals
working in rural parts of the country to treat patients within
their respective areas.
</P>
<P>
Opening the workshop, Vice Minister of the Health Ministry
Lamisso Hayisso said the application of the technology in Ethiopia
would help it curb the problems of health care services it is
facing.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, with a population of 62 million, currently has about
100 hospitals, 3,000 medical centers and clinics throughout the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
