<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Army May Shut Down Weapon Systems to Minimize Y2K Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's military forces will
shut down all computer-controlled weapon systems which fail to
pass the Y2K test before the end of this year to avoid damage or
even disaster, Deputy Army Comptroller Major General Van Anand
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Van admitted that there are delays in the upgrading of the
military's computer systems, but added that the army should not be
blamed.
</P>
<P>
"Y2K correction processes of the Armed Forces' weapons are to
be completed in time before the year 2000 starts if we have
adequate funds," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Army had given priority to fixing its flying and
satellite operations and seven other significant systems, Van
said.
</P>
<P>
Van made the remark after Deputy Prime Minister Trairong
Suwannakhiri warned that an air defense system malfunction might
cause missiles to strike civil aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Trairong said that little was known about the Defense
Ministry's preparedness for the Year 2000 problem and that 65
percent of state agencies had yet to report their progress in
updating computer systems to overcome the problem.
</P>
<P>
Problems are feared at the turn of the new year, because
computer programs written to recognize only the last two digits of
the year might read the digits "00" as 1900 instead of 2000,
causing disruptions from food delivery to power and water
distribution and banking services.
</P>
<P>
The government, especially the Budget Bureau, has been asked to
allocate more funds to government agencies to solve the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
