<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Condemns Namibian Secessionists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan
Mudenge Thursday condemned Namibian guerrilla leaders fighting for
the independence of the remote Caprivi region.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge told the Zimbabwe News Agency that the actions by the
guerrillas were not acceptable because Namibia was a sovereign
state.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly condemn the actions because they are threatening a
country' s integrity and sovereignty. We will never support
that," Mudenge said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe would continue to support the Namibian
government since it was the only recognized government in the
country.
</P>
<P>
About 100 guerrillas led by secessionist Mishake Muyongo
attacked a military base and a television station Monday in
Caprivi's capital Katima Mulilo, killing 15 people in a
street-by-street fighting before being suppressed by the Namibian
army, the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Muyongo was a senior member of the ruling Swapo party during
its exile years but he was expelled from the party in 1980 after
being accused of plotting to topple the Swapo leadership under
current President Sam Nujoma.
</P>
<P>
Caprivi, a 400 km sliver of land wedged between Angola and
Zambia to the north and Botswana to the south, is home to about
100,000 of the country's 1.6 million population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
