<HEADLINE> Angola Positive Toward UN Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Angolan ambassador to the United
Nations said Thursday that the Angolan Government has made a
"positive endorsement" for the UN presence in the southwest
African country.
</P>
<P>
Afonso Van-dunem made the statement in an interview with the
National Radio of Angola, announcing that the Angolan government
has delivered a letter Wednesday to UN Secretary-General Koffi
Annan, "expressly notifying the decision of the government."
</P>
<P>
Van-dunem added that some issues on UN's "physical presence" in
Angola are currently discussed.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador stressed that the Angolan government has been in
favor of a "not so big" UN presence, in correspondence with the
reality of the situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government, then considering UN as a shield for the
 rebellious National Union for Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), demanded a pull-out of the United Nations Observer
Mission in Angola (MONUA) in January, when the government troops
encountered some setbacks in battle fields in the central
provinces of Huambo and Bie.
</P>
<P>
MONUA formally pulled out from the var-torn country on March 1.
 Meanwhile, the UN expressed a will to maintain a mediatory
organization in Angola.
</P>
<P>
But the Angolan government insisted that this kind of
organization should be established in New York, where the UN
headquarters locate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
