<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Improves Telecom Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Telecommunication
Corporation has invested more than 28 million birr (about 3.5
million U.S. dollars) to improve telecommunication service in
southern part of the country, a senior official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Preparations to install new and improve existing communication
equipment in 41 towns in southern Ethiopia next year has been
finalized, senior official with the company, Zerfu Dimtsu said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 41 towns to benefit from the project, 32 towns will be
installed with new telephone lines, while nine towns are to be
equipped new digital exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Some 18,750 residents in southern Ethiopia will have access to
the digital exchanges in the coming Ethiopian budget year starting
from July 9, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zerfu said, most of work on the replacement of the
Addis Ababa microwave with new digital exchange being undertaken
at a cost of 30 million birr (nearly four million U.S. dollars) is
nearing completion.
</P>
<P>
In addition to fixed telephone service, the mobile telephone
service has become available in the Horn of Africa country early
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
