<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Inspects Rescue Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada on Thursday inspected the ongoing rescue and relief work
at a landslide-hit subdivision in Antipolo city, central
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"It's very unfortunate but I'd like to acknowledge the help,
the response given by the people of Antipolo. The assistance
extended by the people here shows that in times of crisis,
Filipinos help each other," he told reporters after the
inspection.
</P>
<P>
The president said he is considering granting assistance to
victims who paid for their houses which were destroyed in the
disaster, Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The disastrous landslide which happened Tuesday night at the
Cherry Hills, Antipolo of Rizal province, hit a subdivision,
killing 26 people, devouring 50 houses and leaving more than 50
buried in the debris -- feared to be dead.
</P>
<P>
A committee charged with tracing out the root cause of the
landslide has been established, mandatory to submit its report to
the Philippine president within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
The subdivision was allegedly built on a patch of loose ground
at the foot of the hill, also a construction jeopardizing the
environment in the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
"This is a lesson to all of us, that before we give a permit,
we see to it that all kinds of requirements will be complied with.
We have to preserve our mountains," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
But he added that he would meet Friday with officials of the
Housing and Urban development Coordinating Council to discuss the
terms of payment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
