<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voice Your Opinion on World Future, Please: Thai FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan Thursday urged the members of the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) to express their
opinion on the world future development.
</P>
<P>
Surin, briefing the diplomatic corps in Thailand on the
preparations for the 10th UNCTAD, asked the members to present
their blueprint for the world development in the next 50 years to
the headquarters of UNCTAD in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will host UNCTAD from February 12-19 next year, which
will be the first global conference of the 21st century and the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The conference will review progress made in the past 50 years,
set developmental strategies for the next 50 years into the 21st
century, consider a design for the new global financial
architecture and equitably integrate developing and least
developed countries into the international economic system, Surin
said.
</P>
<P>
Two historic documents, the Bangkok Declaration and the Bangkok
Plan of Action, will be signed at the end of the conference.
</P>
<P>
The opinions of all the members on the future development of
the world will be contained in the documents after being
deliberated by the conference, said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
There will be about 10,000 people visiting Thailand during the
meeting, including 3,000 to 4,000 delegates from 188 members of
UNCTAD, 1,000 to 2,000 foreign reporters and 3,000 to 4,000 family
members of the delegates and tourists.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD was established in 1964 as a permanent intergovernmental
body. It is the principal organ of the U.N. General Assembly in
the field of trade and development. Its main goals are to maximize
trade, investment and development opportunities of developing
countries, and to help them face challenges arising from
globalization and integrate them into the world economy on an
equitable basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
