<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Conference on Security Ends in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international
conference on security in a changing world ended here on Thursday,
calling for international cooperation based on new concept of
international security.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed that with the change in international
situation and the disappearance of the "bipolar" world, a new
concept of security unlike that during the Cold-War era has
appeared.
</P>
<P>
They held that the concept of international security today
covers not only military security but also a range of other issues
such as economy, the environment, population, transnational crimes,
drugs and epidemic diseases.
</P>
<P>
These issues are difficult to be tackled by a single nation,
they noted, but require concerted efforts of the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Chinese delegate Pang Sen said at the conference that the
international community must have a new concept of security if
they want to safeguard security. They should first of all abide
by the objectives and principles of the U.N. Charter, particularly
the five principles of peaceful coexistence that govern the
relations between nations.
</P>
<P>
They must also respect the sovereignty and territorial
integrity of different countries and in particular refrain from
intervening in the internal affairs of other nations and resorting
to force to settle international conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He said that security can not be secured by expanding military
alliances or intensifying arms race. The proper way to safeguard
security is to strengthen international cooperation and dialogues,
enhance mutual understanding and trust and solve differences by
peaceful means, he added.
</P>
<P>
About 60 delegates from the United Nations and more than 30
countries, including China, Russia, the United States, France and
Britain, attended the conference, which was jointly sponsored by
Mongolia and the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
