<HEADLINE> China Maps Out Judicial Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 5 (Xinhua)-- China will take steps to promote
judicial reform in the next five years in an effort to ensure the
sound functioning of the people's courts and accomplish the
strategic goal of establishing "the rule of law."
</P>
<P>
China's top judge, Xiao Yang, revealed the draft plan here
today at a forum attended by presidents of the country's higher
people's courts.
</P>
<P>
The plan touches upon the reform of trial procedures, court
restructuring, the improvement of the people's jury system, and
supervisory mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
The overall objective of the reform is to create a fair, open,
effective, honest and well-functioning judicial system, train
qualified judges and perfect the socialist judicial system with
Chinese characteristics, said Xiao, president of the Supreme
People's Court.
</P>
<P>
The reform should be based on the three principles of upholding
the Chinese Communist Party's leadership, the People's Congress
system, and the integration of the country's judicial system, Xiao
said.
</P>
<P>
The top judge stressed that the reform encourages bold steps in
accordance with the Constitution and laws, and opposes judicial
independence and supremacy, which exist in many Western countries.
</P>
<P>
"Court reform represents a major part of China's reform of the
judicial system and political restructuring. The essence of
judicial reform is judicial fairness, which is crucial to the
country's rule of law," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Sets Up Economic Surveillance System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) has set up an economic surveillance system
designed to avert future financial crises and encourage the
members to reform their economies.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, ministers and officials of the ASEAN members
would exchange data and share opinions on economic trends and
macroeconomic policies in the region, ASEAN Secretary-General
Rodolfo Severino said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A unit in the ASEAN Secretariat was established early this year
to manage the process, with support from the Asian Development
Bank (ADB), in which a counterpart unit operates, he told
reporters in Pulau Pinang, northern Malaysia, after the opening of
a regional conference on a common currency for East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian national news agency Bernama quoted him as saying
that data and analysis collected by the unit would be forwarded to
ASEAN financial ministers to look at and they would seek ways to
prevent economic crises in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
The unit and the ADB earlier issued the first report which
included measures to stimulate finance, protect the poor, mobilize
additional resources for economic recovery and improve the
reformation of the financial sector. It will issue another report
sometime in September, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the common currency for ASEAN, Severino said ASEAN has taken
steps to cooperate in the financial area short of creating a
common currency and has been encouraging the use of ASEAN
currencies in the settlement of intra-ASEAN trade.
</P>
<P>
This is to be done largely through bilateral payment
arrangements and Malaysia and the Philippines have concluded one
such arrangement while others are under negotiation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that to have an ASEAN currency, the regional economies
have to be sufficiently integrated, rivalries and mutual
suspicions lingering from history have to be overcome and
questions of sovereignty have to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's leaders have called for the development of capital
markets in the region so as to reduce ASEAN's dependence on
developed countries, and have decided to cooperate in improving
the regulation and transparency of the financial system.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 participants comprising academicians, researchers,
policymakers, representatives of governmental and non-governmental
organizations from ASEAN countries, China, South Korea and Japan
are attending the three-day conference.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
