<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Judge New NATO Chief by Deeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Thursday that it would
take further foreign policy steps toward NATO and its new
secretary-general, George Robertson, after judging them "by their
concrete deeds."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said Moscow
regards Robertson's appointment as an internal affair of the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
He said Robertson is well known in Russian military-political
circles mainly due to contacts with him when he was the British
defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Russia already noticed Robertson's
statement on the importance of a business-like relationship
between NATO and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment Russian-NATO cooperation is limited to
international peacekeeping operations in Kosovo and Bosnia while
all other spheres of cooperation remain frozen," Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
As for the future of Russia-NATO contacts, he said Moscow
speaks of "straightening out relations under certain conditions,"
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Moscow "wants primarily that the Yugoslav tragedy connected
with the military operation of the alliance in the Balkans never
to be repeated, that new dividing lines will not be drawn in
Europe as a result of the implementation of NATO enlargement plans,
that the alliance fully takes into account our lawful interests
and concerns and strictly follows the provisions of the Russia-
NATO founding act," Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming Robertson's statement on the importance of
ties between NATO and Russia, Moscow was concerned by his
announcement that NATO's eastward enlargement will be the
cornerstone of his work as the political leader of the alliance.
</P>
