<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Claims Big Gains in Counter Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan opposition Thursday
claimed to have recaptured half of the area they had lost and
inflicted heavy casualties on the ruling Taliban militia in a
dramatic overnight counter offensive.
</P>
<P>
No comment from the Taliban was available.
</P>
<P>
Opposition spokesman Abdullah (only one name) said their forces
recaptured Jabul Saraj, Charikar and Gulbahar north of the capital
Kabul in a surprise strike on Wednesday night and Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
At least 250 Taliban fighters were killed while dozens of
prisoners were taken, said Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
However, General Sayed Husain Anwari, a commander from the
Harakat-i-Islami faction of the northern opposition alliance,
alleged that between 400 and 500 Taliban troops were killed in the
surprise offensive.
</P>
<P>
Among the 250 dead were large numbers of Arabs and Pakistanis,
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdullah, the opposition troops had moved out of
the heavily fortified Panjsher valley late Wednesday night and
taken Gulbahar near the western entrance of the valley before
advancing west to the Northern Highway at Jabul Saraj.
</P>
<P>
After taking Jabul Saraj at 8 a.m. Thursday local time, they
moved southwards and circled around Charikar and cut the exit
route before taking the capital of Parwan province at around 10:30
a.m.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban were asleep when we moved in," Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan opposition forces were now at the crossroads of the
New Roads and the Old Roads to the west of the strategic Bagram
air base, some 50 kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The opposition said it expected to recapture the Bagram air
base soon which was now under attack from two positions.
</P>
<P>
In a separate operation, opposition troops attacked the town of
Nejrab, to the south of the Panjsher valley, from the province of
Kapisa, sources from Kabul said.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan sources said the Taliban also lost a substantial
number of men in these battles.
</P>
<P>
Controlling nearly 90 percent of Afghanistan, the Taliban
launched the long-awaited summer offensive last Wednesday and
captured a number of strategic points like Nejrab, Bagram,
Charikar and Jabul Saraj during the past week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
