<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Visit US Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit is expected to pay an official visit to the United States
in September.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources here said Ecevit will hold talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton and other top U.S. officials on the
situation in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. has dispatched warplanes to bombard the facilities in
northern Iraq from the Incirlik Air Base in Adana, southern
Turkey, since the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will also focus on the Cyprus issue and the need
for improved relations between Turkey and Greece, both members of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
U.S. National Security Council Spokesman David Leavy has said
that "resolving Cyprus is a key priority for the administration,"
and Washington is encouraged by both sides' willingness to hold
negotiations this fall.
</P>
<P>
After a call by the group of seven most industrialized
countries and Russia (G8) issued in June, U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan appealed to Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas to resume the deadlocked
Cyprus talks in October in New York.
</P>
<P>
Denktas has been insisting that the Cyprus talks, which has
been stalled since 1997 with the start of accession talks between
Cyprus and the European Union (EU), could resume only on a
state-to-state level -- a demand tantamount to asking for
recognition of the "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, who was then the Turkish prime minister in 1974,
ordered the Turkish troops to invade Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, during Ecevit's visit to the U.S., the two leaders
will also discuss the situation in the Balkans and the growing
role of Turkey in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
