<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU: "Yellow Rice" to Prevent Vitamin A Deficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said on
Thursday that scientists for a project funded by the European
Union (EU) has created a kind of "yellow rice" which will help
prevent severe vitamin A deficiency in countries relying on rice
as a staple food.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body said that under the so-called "Carotene
plus" project, scientists have succeeded in modifying rice through
genetic engineering to make it produce beta-carotene which is
converted to vitamin A by humans.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the carotene content, the rice turns yellow.
This kind of rice can be considered as a functional food -- a new
category of food products providing specific health benefits, the
commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The rice contains enough beta-carotene to meet total vitamin A
requirements in a typical Asian diet, it added. It means that
Asian countries would benefit from the rice in their bid to
prevent vitamin A deficiency.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that vitamin A deficiency is a public health
problem in 118 countries. It not only causes xerophthalmia, the
leading factor of childhood blindness in developing countries, but
also has broader consequences in terms of child morbidity and
mortality by leading to greater susceptibility to various diseases
such as respiratory infections, diarrhea and measles.
</P>
<P>
Between 140 and 250 million pre-school children are deficient
in vitamin A worldwide, according to the World Health Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Better Donor System Urged for Kidney Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- More people in Canada than ever
before are suffering from kidney failure, prompting renewed calls
for bettering the country's "fragmented" donor transplant system,
a newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Citing the Canadian Institute for Health Information, the "
National Post" said that the dialysis population is rising by up
to 14 percent a year, a 200 percent increase since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Only 14.4 donors per million Canadians donate their organs, in
contrast with 31 donors per million in Spain, the newspaper said,
adding that the number of Canadians on the waiting list for a
kidney transplant exceeds 2,800, at a growing rate of 12-14
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
Kidney disease is reported to become the sixth leading cause of
death in Canada, with a daily average of eight new patients
diagnosed with renal failure.
</P>
<P>
"Elderly patients accounted for most of that increase," the
institute sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statistics put pressure for the establishment of a Canadian
transplant network, covering donor consent, determination of brain
death of donors and national standards for tissue safety, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Health Minister Allan Rock is expected to make a
decision on a national program in September in response to a
Commons committee report on organ and tissue donation tabled in
April, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
