<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislation on Voluntary Service by Youngsters Passed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
Guangdong Provincial People's Congress today passed legislation
detailing stipulations for voluntary service by young people.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, titled "Regulation on Voluntary Service by
Young People of Guangdong Province," is the first of its kind in
China. The regulation will become effective as of September 20,
said local sources.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, young volunteers should be aged
between 16 and 35, and should first be registered in young
volunteers associations set up in various localities.
</P>
<P>
It is also necessary that young volunteers be identified by the
organization they represent before they provide volunteer services.
Youngsters aged 16 to 18 are encouraged to offer up to 100 hours
of volunteer service.
</P>
<P>
Young volunteers associations will also bear civil
responsibility in cases of any damages caused by the young
volunteers from their associations, and compensation for
deliberate or major damage can be recovered.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, those with a history of voluntary
service will be given priority in employment and enrollment for
advanced studies.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, in the forefront of China's reform and opening-up
drive, was one of the first regions in the country to institute
voluntary service.
</P>
<P>
One million young volunteers in this south Chinese province
have offered voluntary services ranging from major events and
poverty relief in the countryside to neighborhood labor since 1987,
when Guangzhou, the provincial capital, opened a hotline for
middle school students by which young teachers were made available,
free of charge, to help troubled middle school students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Kicks Off National Survey of Petroleum Products Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- China has formally launched a
national survey of the quality of petroleum products processed by
small refineries.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Administration of Petroleum and Chemical
Industries (SAPCI), the small refineries being checked are those
with an annual crude processing capacity of less than one million
tons. The products quality inspection of the first group of
refineries, including 57 small refineries, began on August 2 and
is scheduled to last until the end of September. The second group
to be examined will include 23 refineries, and that inspection is
expected to be completed before the end of October.
</P>
<P>
An official with SAPCI said that during the inspections, the
quality of major petroleum products, including gasoline, diesel,
asphalt, solvent oil, and lubricating oil, will be checked in
compliance with State standards. Those found to be producing
substandard products will be closed down.
</P>
<P>
The survey is being conducted by the Center for Petroleum
Quality Inspection which operates under the China Petrochemical
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
This national survey is part of China's move to create a
regulated petroleum product distribution sector to replace the one
which has long been plagued by products of inferior quality. The
closing down of substandard refineries will, on the other hand,
help build a more competitive petrochemical industry, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China had 166 small refineries,
accounting for 75 percent of the national total. However, their
combined crude processing capacity was 30.8 million tons a year,
making up less than 12 percent of the country's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
