<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Cost China Over Eight Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Floods this summer have hit a
majority of Chinese provinces and regions, leaving 725 people dead
and causing 66.8 billion yuan (8.05 billion U.S. dollars) in
direct economic losses, according to the latest official figures.
</P>
<P>
According to information released today by the Ministry of
Civil Affairs, 23 of China's provinces, autonomous regions, and
municipalities have been struck by floods.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, over 5.53 million Chinese have been relocated
and 1.67 million homes destroyed, while some 11.31 million
hectares of crops have been affected, with 1.56 million hectares
being expected to yield nothing this year.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same period of last year, this year's flood-
stricken population is about 58.8 percent that of last year, death
toll about 28.8 percent, destroyed homes 30.2 percent, and direct
economic losses 36.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and the State
Council have been giving great attention to disaster fighting and
relief work, according to the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Ministry of Civil Affairs and the Ministry of
Finance have appropriated 117 million yuan and over 9,000 special
tents for disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
The ministries of water resources, communications, education,
and agriculture have also provided 845 million yuan as well as
chemical fertilizers and diesel oil for flood control and
prevention, and other disaster relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
