<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Build Asia's Key Trade Information Internet Web-site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC) has launched a multi-million dollar campaign to
build Asia's key trade information Internet web-site, in a bid to
help Hong Kong become Asia's cyber trade hub.
</P>
<P>
In his address to a seminar on small and medium-sized
enterprises Thursday, Victor Fung, chairman of TDC, said Hong Kong
is now faced with a major challenge to replicate in cyberspace,
the current gateway function Hong Kong provides for trade in the
physical world.
</P>
<P>
"Just as Hong Kong handles 40 percent of all physical trade
moving to and from the Chinese mainland, so must we strive, in the
future, to handle a significant share of the world's 'cyber trade'
with the mainland," Fung noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the TDC has invested 180 million HK dollars (23 million
U.S. dollars) in upgrading its IT infrastructure -- putting in
place more sophisticated computer systems and software.
</P>
<P>
In the past couple of years, the TDC moved market intelligence
and economic information to the web site, and opened online trade-
matching services to global participation, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's ability to compete in this new world will depend
on how successfully we leverage, in cyberspace, our existing
skills as the chief intermediator of trade and investment in Asia,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the TDC will offer strategic links to other key
sites in Hong Kong and the region, making it more attractive for
global business partners to enter Asia's cyberspace through Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We will expand and deepen the market intelligence we gather
from TDC's global network of 50 offices," he said. "We will
liberalize access to our database of trade contacts and liberalize
our fee structures, so that customers will no longer pay to use
our standard Internet-based services, including trade inquiries."
</P>
</TEXT>
