<HEADLINE> Canadian Farmers Reported on Brink of Worst Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Canadian farmers say they're in
for the worst crisis since the Great Depression of the 1930s
because of sluggish commodity prices, high expenses and wacky
weather, CTV said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The farmers appeal for government support while federal
agricultural officials say that they are not there to bail out the
farmers, who are suffering drought in the east and excessive rain
in prairie, the report said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Canadian Federation of Agriculture demanded
Ottawa and the provinces commit to developing a permanent disaster
assistance program to avoid a rural meltdown.
</P>
<P>
Bob Friesen, president of the federation, warned at a news
conference "Canada is going to lose a lot of farmers, a lot of
jobs and see many of its rural communities disintegrate over the
next five years without a firm commitment of long-term support."
</P>
<P>
Statistics Canada has warned that net farm income will be cut
by almost half this year, dropping to 1.78 billion Canadian
dollars (about 1.19 billion U.S. dollars), as compared to an
annual average of 3.33 billion (about 2.23 billion U.S. dollars)
between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
A national safety nets advisory committee was reported to look
into the issue at meetings slated for Thursday and Friday in
Ottawa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
