<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Parliament President Asked to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- By an unanimous vote, Nigerian
House of Representatives Wednesday asked Senate President Evan
Enwerem to step aside, for an unimpeded probe of allegations of
stealing currently dogging his heels.
</P>
<P>
The heat on the Senate president also intensified, with a call
by Alliance for Democracy (AD) that he resigns, reported the
Guardian, a Nigerian Newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Allegations were made in the latest edition published this
week's Tell, a Lagos based magazine, saying that the Senate
president was convicted for stealing in 1945 while serving as a
revenue clerk under the British colonial government and variously
falsified his age for public office.
</P>
<P>
Enwerem has consistently denied the allegations and described
it as part of a campaign to "bring me down and ridicule the
office".
</P>
<P>
Like a replay of political currents that swept former House of
 Representatives Speaker, Alhaji Ibrahim Salisu Buhari from
office, representatives Wednesday held that because the National
Assembly's integrity was at stake, Enwerem will do well by
allowing his deputy, Alhaji Haruna Abubakar, preside over the
Senate's affairs "until the grave allegations are cleared."
</P>
<P>
Besides, the legislators directed the committee on ethics and
privileges; national security and intelligence; judiciary, human
rights and legal matters to investigate and ascertain the truth of
the matter and submit its findings to the house within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Members held a closed door session for one and a half hours
Wednesday before the house began formal proceedings. A member said
it was to enable the legislature address "emergency house
matters" and tighten loose ends on the motions on notice.
</P>
<P>
Moving the motion for Enwerem to step aside, Hon. Adams Jagaba
(Kachia/ Kagarko; Kaduna) prayed the house to consider the option
"in view of the allegations leveled against the Senate president
in the current issue of Tell magazine, which not only question the
integrity of the National Assembly, but can also endanger the
political life of this administration."
</P>
<P>
The legislator argued: "We are our brother's keepers in the
National Assembly," saying the House needed to demonstrate
considerable concern in whatever is happening in any of the
legislative houses.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's motion was amended upon the insistence of some
legislators, led by Hon. Nduka Irabor (Ika; Delta) to include the
investigation of "all other (similar) matters within a reasonable
time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
