<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Report: Sanctions Severely Affect Iraqi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 5 (Xinhua) -- An international report has
revealed that the mortality of Iraqi children under five exceeded
12.2 percent due to the nine-year U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the U.N. Children Fund said malnutrition of
mothers caused a birth rate of under-weight infants at more than
23.8 percent last year, the Iraqi News Agency reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that 14.7 percent of infants suffer from
malnutrition diseases, 11.7 percent from chronic malnutrition and
8.2 percent from acute malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the embargo caused an increase of congenital
deformity, infection diseases and high fever due to shortage in
necessary treatment.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that so many Iraqi families are always
worried about how to feed their children because food provided
under the oil-for-food program covers needs of the Iraqi people
only for 20 days every month.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to export limited amount of
oil in every six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 24 million people.
</P>
<P>
The embargo deprived the Iraqi children of enjoying the widest
opportunities of education and practicizing their games and
possessing books compatible with their mentalities and physical
capabilities, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It said the social care programs in Iraq have suffered from
many hardships in the past nine years due to the U.N. sanctions
imposed the country following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The 1991 Gulf War and the continuation of embargo led to the
destruction of a number of state orphanages and several
educational and nutritional services offered by the social care
institutes, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
