<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Youths to Attend Dragon Project for New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong youths will join the
mainland Chinese young people in demonstrating their determination
and commitment to meet the challenges of the new millennium
through the "Dragon at the Great Wall" project.
</P>
<P>
Jointly organized by the All-China Youth Federation of China
and "Dragon at the Great Wall" Hong Kong Committee, and sponsored
by the Home Affairs Department and the Hong Kong Federation of
Youth Groups, the Dragon project is one of the major events to
celebrate the advent of the new millennium, which happens to fall
on the Year of the Dragon, the most auspicious of the 12 signs of
the Chinese zodiac.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the large-scale youth project at a press conference
Thursday, Secretary for home affairs David Lan said: "With the
approach of the Year of the Dragon, it is particularly timely to
organize the 'Dragon at the Great Wall' project in 2000. As it not
only signifies the unity and solidarity of the Chinese youth, but
also provides a vision into the new millennium which would help
prepare for the future development of the youth."
</P>
<P>
The project comprises three parts, namely the Dragon Dance at
the Great Wall, the Youth Conference on Meeting the Challenges of
the New Millennium and the Dragon Foundation.
</P>
<P>
In February 2000, 10,000 Chinese youths from the mainland, Hong
Kong, Macao, Taiwan and overseas will gather to raise a 10,000
foot long dragon at the Ba Da Ling section of the Great Wall. It
is expected to set a new world record which will be televised live
around the world.
</P>
<P>
The Youth Conference, also to be held in February 2000, will be
attended by Chinese participants from the mainland, Hong Kong,
Macao, Taiwan and overseas to identify the trends of global
development in the next century, paying special attention to
issues that directly affect young people.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the "Dragon at the Great Wall" project, a variety of
spectacular and colorful celebrations will be organized from
December 1999 to mid-2000, including the Millennium Extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
The Millennium Extravaganza will kick off on New Year's Eve and
continue throughout the night to early hours of the New Year's Day
at Hong Kong's Happy Valley Race Course.
</P>
<P>
One of the highlights will be an impressive pyrotechnic
display. The 1,400-meter long pyrotechnic display, which might
gain a new entry in the Guinness Book of World Records, will light
up the whole venue to mark the beginning of a new era for the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
