<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overuse Of Groundwater Causing Subsidence In North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The excessive use of
groundwater in north China has caused depressions in the land in
some areas.
</P>
<P>
A provincial water control official says that 11 such "funnels"
have been found not far beneath the surface of the earth in Hebei
Province over 9,000 sq.km. of ground. The water table has been
sinking at an annual rate of one to two meters since the 1980s,
causing further depressions over some 30,900 sq.km. of land.
</P>
<P>
Water shortages get most of the blame for this situation, as
Hebei has 17 billion cubic meters of usable water, compared with
an average annual demand of 20 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The falling water levels may cause the ground to crack, sink
more, and ultimately cave in. So far, more than 200 crevices have
been found on the plains of Hebei, some running for thousands of
meters and as deep as ten meters.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials say this situation is dangerous, and point
to the past when sinking ground damaged buildings, drainage
systems, and dikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
