<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 19 New AIDS Cases Found in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen new AIDS cases were
reported in the second quarter of 1999 in Hong Kong, bringing to a
total of 409 confirmed AIDS cases since 1985, the Department of
Health (DH) announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for DH said that some 63 person were also found to
be positive for the HIV antibody test in the same quarter,
bringing the cumulative total number of reported HIV infections to
1,255.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 63 new HIV infections, 32 were sexually acquired with
heterosexual contact which remains the major route of transmission.
fourteen of them admitted themselves to be homosexuals or
bisexuals," said Doctor Chan Ching-nin, a senior medical officer
from the DH Special Preventive Program.
</P>
<P>
He said that two mother-to-child infections were also diagnosed,
another three were injecting drug users and one was infused HIV
contaminated blood product before 1985.
</P>
<P>
As for the remaining 11 cases, the information available was
inadequate for classification, he said.
</P>
<P>
For the second quarter, the ratio of reported male to female
HIV infections was 6 to 1, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
"Actually AIDS is not only a medical problem. It involves a lot
of sectors, including medical and social educationalists. We will
work hand in hand to fight back the AIDS issue in Hong Kong in the
future."
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to have our input to the education effort in
combating the AIDS," Chan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
