<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Parties Concerned to Expand Positive Factors on Korean Peninsular Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Qian Yongnian
urged here Thursday the parties concerned to strive to expand
positive factors, minimize and remove destabilizing factors so as
to bring the Korean Peninsula closer to stability.
</P>
<P>
"Positive and destabilizing factors coexist on the peninsula,"
Qian, who chairs the current five-day meeting, said in the keynote
address to the sixth plenary session of the Four-Party Talks on
the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from China, the United States, the Democratic
Republic of Korea (DPRK) and the Republic of Korea (ROK) initiated
the Four-Party talks in Geneva in late 1997 to discuss the
establishment of a peace regime on the Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
As positive factors, Qian recalled, the DPRK and the U.S. have
maintained their dialogue and contact, and the DPRK and ROK have
recently resumed their talks at the vice ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
"Although no progress has been made in the talks, the frank
exchange of views itself on relevant issues between the north and
the south is useful for better communication and understanding,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he said, "the destabilizing factors on the
peninsula warrant our attention," adding that the standoff between
DPRK and ROK warships on the Yellow Sea in June, which escalated
to armed clash and caused casualties, put the peninsula under
great tension once again.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that relevant parties could learn useful
lessons from the current situation on the peninsula, strive to
expand the positive factors, minimize and remove destabilizing
factors so as to bring the peninsula closer to stability," Qian
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
