<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eloi Ousts Wang in Table Tennis Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Frenchman Damien
Eloi played an extremely aggressive game to beat Chinese star Wang
Liqin convincingly at the world table tennis championships here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 21st-ranked Eloi, known for playing well in the clutches,
handed a 21-13, 21-18, 21-17 defeat to the player hailed as
champion-elect by Chinese media.
</P>
<P>
Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua was so angry with Wang's loss that
he billed his best student as a "choker".
</P>
<P>
"How could he play like this? His brain must have got stuck," Cai
said.
</P>
<P>
Wang could not cope with the whirlwind at the other end of the
table as Eloi blasted winner after winner and finally hit yet
another brilliant forehand on match point to enter the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
Wang stormed out of the court after the match and begged Shanghai
reporters not to interview him at this moment. Wang is also from
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"I am not in the mood for interview, please leave me alone," Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
Later Wang told reporters that he could not find rhythm during the
match and his poor returns to Elois' serves cost him dearly.
</P>
<P>
Eloi's forehand attack is as strong as his mentality. He had
stretched Chinese star Wang Tao to five sets in the 1995 world
championships, and extended the Chinese to 29-29 in the 1995 world
championship team final which was won by China.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus edged out Dutchman Danny
Heister to join defending champion Jan-Ove Waldner of Sweden in the
last 16. Waldner nipped He Zhiwen of Spain 18-21, 21-14, 21-15,
21-14.
</P>
<P>
Two-time World Cup winner Zoran Primorac of Croatia advanced with
a five-set win over Chinese teenager Liu Guozheng.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Kong Linghui, 1995 world champion and World Cup winner,
thumped Canadian Johnny Huang in straight sets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
