<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Inflation Remains at 5.7 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' year-on-year
inflation rate stood at 5.7 percent in July, unchanged from the
previous month, mainly due to lower food prices, the National
Statistics Office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The July figure brought the country's inflation rate in the
first seven months of this year to 8 percent, well within the
government target range of 8 percent to 9 percent for the whole
year, the office said in a report issued here.
</P>
<P>
"The inflation rate for food alone moved down to 3.2 percent in
July from 3.3 percent in June. Lower rates were posted in the
prices of rice, 3.5 percent from 3.6 percent; cereal preparations,
3.9 percent from 4.5 percent; dairy products, 3.3 percent from 3.4
percent..." the office said.
</P>
<P>
The office noted that the rates for housing and repairs slowed
down to 9.3 percent in July from 9.6 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, it said, the rates increased for services to
11.1 percent in July from 10.7 percent in June, and fuel, light
and water rose to 5.7 percent from 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, the country's month-on-month inflation
in July rose by 0.2 percent, compared to 0.8 percent registered
for June.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of the Philippines said that the unchanged
year-on-year inflation rate in July has reinforced its position
that there is more room for interest rates to fall.
</P>
<P>
At present, the central bank's overnight borrowing rates have
been lowered to 9 percent and 11 percent respectively, the lowest
in the last two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
