<HEADLINE> Chinese, Australian Scientists Fight Against Mice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua)-- Scientists from China and
Australia will cooperate in a campaign against mice, which will
greatly benefit agricultural and stock breeding in both countries.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was signed recently between the Wildlife and
Ecology Institute of the Australian Common Wealth Scientific and
Industrial Research Organization (CWSIRO) and the Institute of
Zoology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS). Their
collaboration will focus on the development of a bacteria that
will sterilize mice.
</P>
<P>
The patterns of disasters caused by mice and their forecasting
also will be studied. Scientists indicate that this joint effort
will greatly contribute to the fight against mice in both China
and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Mice can cause great damage to agricultural and stock breeding
anywhere in the world. In China, about 24.7 million hectares of
farmland and 37.3 million hectares of pasture are destroyed by
mice every year, causing the loss of 10 billion kilograms of grain
and 20 billion kilograms of herbage.
</P>
<P>
Plagues caused by mice frequently occur in India, Pakistan, and
several countries in Southeast Asia, while in China, more than 100,
000 people are affected by epidemic diseases caused by mice each
year.
</P>
<P>
Experts indicate that the use of chemical poisons to deal with
these problems is not effective in the long run, and can cause
environmental pollution. So the development of a mice-control
bacteria has drawn some attention all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The Institute of Zoology of the CAS began research on mice DNA
in 1995. And the Wildlife and Ecology Institute under Australia's
CWSIRO has achieved a breakthrough in developing a bacteria to
control house mice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
