<HEADLINE> Howard Confident of Republic Referendum Being On Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard Thursday played down chances that the country's republic
referendum could be delayed if the Labor Party and the Democrats
Party tried to change the wording of the question.
</P>
<P>
Howard told reporters that he expected more talks on the issue
with the Democrats but remained confident that the referendum
question would pass through parliament in time.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to keep my word on that and if anybody tries to stop
me keeping my word, well, it will be on their head, not on mine,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The only people who can stop me doing that is the Senate and I
don't think it will do that," he added.
</P>
<P>
An all-party committee has recommended that the referendum
question spell out how a president will replace the queen as the
head of state.
</P>
<P>
The Democrats will hold a party room meeting on Monday to
formalize their stand. The Labor Party is expected to support the
revised question.
</P>
<P>
The parliament has to agree with the form of the question by
the end of next week for the referendum to go ahead on November 6.
</P>
<P>
Howard also repeated earlier comments that he was not concerned
that several ministers, including Treasurer Peter Costello and
Industrial Relations Minister Peter Reith, continued to disagree
over the republic move.
</P>
<P>
"As individuals, my ministers, senior or otherwise, have a
right to express their views," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
