<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Repeats with Correction China Chairs Sixth-round Talks on Korean Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Qian Yongnian
opened the sixth plenary session of the four-party talks on the
Korean peninsula here Thursday by expressing hope that the current
round would result in substantive development.
</P>
<P>
As chairman of the sixth plenary, Qian said in the keynote
address that much progress has been made since the representatives
of China, the United States, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) and the Republic of Korea began to discuss the
establishment of a peace regime on the peninsula in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the five previous plenaries and the three preparatory
meetings, the parties elaborated their respective positions on
tension reduction, establishment of peace regime and realization
of lasting peace and stability on the peninsula, set up two
subcommittees for the purpose and held useful discussions on
substantive issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he noted, the progress has been falling far
short of the aspiration and expectation of the peace-loving people
in the region and around the globe.
</P>
<P>
"It is still far from reaching the talks' ultimate objectives,"
Qian said. "What is more worrying is that in the process of the
talks, incidents of military conflict have cropped up from time to
time on the peninsula, adding new destabilizing factors there."
</P>
</TEXT>
