<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Criticizes BBC, VOA for Destabilization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
strongly condemned the activities of the Hausa services of the BBC
and the VOA, describing both stations as "agents of
destabilization and enemies of our nascent democracy".
</P>
<P>
Special Assistant to the President on Media and Publicity,
Doyin Okupe, expressed the anger of the government against these
stations on Wednesday in Kaduna, northern Nigeria, according to a
New Nigerian report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said, "it is unthinkable that these, otherwise respectable
organizations, should allow themselves to be used so readily by
those who want to destabilize Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
Okupe, spokesman for the presidency, said that "we are
convinced that these stations are deliberately out to create
anarchy in the country."
</P>
<P>
It was unfortunate that rather than assisting the nation in the
 difficult tasks ahead, the Hausa broadcasts created and
propagated confusion and give access only to those who fanned the
ember of ethnicity and religion, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The normal ideals of journalism, which encourage fairness and
balancing of the views, should be respected, the spokesman said,
but there is lack of balance in BBC and VOA Hausa news programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
