<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Allowed to Deal in Yuan in More Chinese Localities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign banks are now allowed to
handle Chinese yuan-based business in China's Jiangsu, Zhejiang,
Guangdong and Hunan provinces, and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, a spokesman with the Shanghai Branch of the People's Bank
of China, the country's central bank, announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Restrictions on the use of the yuan in interbank lending and
the organizing of consortia by foreign banks have also been
loosened, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Previously, foreign banks could only deal in the yuan in the
cities of Shanghai and Shenzhen, on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
Local experts called this move a new step by China toward
opening its financial sector to the outside world, adding that it
also provides good business opportunities for overseas banks.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, there were 253 representative offices
of overseas banks and 173 operational overseas banking
institutions in China, with aggregate assets of 34.2 billion U.S.
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
