<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Sharply Lower on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Share prices nose-dived on
Singapore Stock Market Thursday on fears of a possible rise of the
U.S. interest rate and in tandem with regional exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) plunged by 61.87 points
to the week low of 2,082.13 points in light dealings.
</P>
<P>
The total volume contracted to 231 million shares valued at
470.02 million Singapore dollars (280.70 million U.S. dollars).
The decliners outstripped advancers by 321 to 28 with 94 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DelMonte was the most active stock as it registered a turnover
of 12.92 million stocks. AFP was the second most heavily traded
stock with 11.58 million shares changing hands. GoldenAG was the
next having 10.25 million counters traded.
</P>
<P>
Asean headed the ascent of the day as it gained 50 cents to
close at 9.50 Singapore dollars. SIA F climbed up 30 cents to
finish at 16.70 Singapore dollars. ANA Ho picked up nine cents to
end at 2.76 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH and SPH 100 led the losers of the day
dropping 160 cents to finish at 29.10 and 29.20 Singapore dollars
respectively. DBS F plunged by 120 cents to finish at 21.00
Singapore dollars. DBS and OCBC sank 70 cents each to end at 18.10
and 12.30 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said prolonged fear of a possible hike in the U.S.
interest rate kept investors being cautious and remaining on
sidelines, and discouraged the market buying.
</P>
<P>
They also said falls in regional bourses contributed to the
weaker sentiment.
</P>
<P>
They predicted investors were likely to refrain from active
buying with the long weekend ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
