<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- According to a survey published on Wednesday by the state
statistics and economics study institute INSEE, the morale of
French households has reached its highest in 12 years. The French
consumers showed in the monthly survey made in July that they are
confident about employment, financial situation and the capacity
of saving money.
</P>
<P>
-- Belgium has been greatly moved by an open letter found on
the two young Guineans who were killed by coldness during their
flight to Europe in a landing train of an Airbus of the Belgian
Sabena air company early this week. The two teenagers, Yaguine
Koita and Fode Tounkara, appealed to the "excellent misters, the
members and leaders of Europe" to help Africa out of war, disease
and poverty.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- George Robertson, a 53-year-old Scottish Highlander, was
nominated on Wednesday with unanimity by the council of
ambassadors of the 19 NATO member countries to be the new
secretary general of the alliance. Robertson, a protege of British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, won the post because of his
intransigent and unconditional support to the "Lonely Ranger"
operation against Iraq and the NATO operation over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
-- Eritrea has been heavily enrolling women into its army in
the fratricide war with Ethiopia. Women, who now make up 30
percent of the Erytrean army, have been forced to fight in the
trenches in the civil wars of Ethiopia in the past 30 years,
including the war against the regime of Mengistu, "the red Negus,"
which led to the independence of Eritrea in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
