<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lanka Publicizes Fax Numbers for Reporting Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka said Thursday that it
4
has decided to make public two fax numbers for people to report
corruption acts in view of the inability of a bribery commission.
</P>
<P>
Any person could fax information directly to the country's
president by the two numbers during 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. on any day of
the week, the Presidential Secretariat said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Bribery Commission which was set up with wide-ranging
powers to investigate allegations of corruption proved to be
unduly slow, completing only five investigations in a period of
three and a half years," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said the commission had also failed to prosecute
successfully a single case of corruption between December 1994 and
August 1997.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the commission has now been embroiled in
internal problems which have paralyzed all its actions.
</P>
<P>
As an interim measure, the government has decided to let the
public directly inform the president of any suspicion or knowledge
of corruption at any level of public authority in the country,
including ministers, deputy ministers, members of parliament,
public officials, the armed forces and the police.
</P>
<P>
The fax machines will be maintained under strict security
conditions and the information received will be treated strictly
and confidentially, the statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
