<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Scientists to Conduct Tests During Solar Eclipse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists will carry
out a host of experiments during this millennium's last total
solar eclipse (TSE) on August 11.
</P>
<P>
Among the experiments, the Indian Institute of Astrophysics
(IIA) in Bangalore would conduct one to know why solar corona is
many times hotter than the sun's surface, a fact that is puzzling
scientists for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
"The experiment will be carried out at a place 400 kilometers
away from Teheran in Iran where the duration of totality is about
two minutes and the sky is expected to be the best," IIA Director
Ramanath Cowsik said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A highly sophisticated instrument indigenously developed by the
institute was set up at Teheran a week ago and scientists were now
fine-tuning it, he said.
</P>
<P>
The instrument, called imaging photometer, will be used to
probe the solar corona, the upper rarefied solar atmosphere which
becomes visible around a dark sun during the TSE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels Deny Surrender of Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Congolese rebels fighting to
remove President Laurent Kabila from power have dismissed reports
that over 1,000 rebels surrendered to government forces in Katanga
Province in southeast of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
''This is absolutely false, no such massive surrender took
place,'' said Commander Jean Pierre Ondekane, deputy president of
the main rebel group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD), who
told Rwanda News Agency in a telephone interview from the rebel
stronghold of Goma Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ondekane accused Kabila of capitalizing on lies all along the
one-year old conflict as a weapon to boost the morale of his
forces.
</P>
<P>
''This is mere propaganda by Kinshasa aimed at hoodwinking the
national and international opinion about the course of war,''
Ondekane underlined.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Kinshasa had also claimed that 3,000 rebel soldiers
had surrendered to loyalist forces in Kabila's home town of
Manono, in Katanga.
</P>
<P>
The RCD rebels had refuted the claims and said that only 41
prisoners of war out of 250 captured early in the fighting had
vanished in villages while they were being evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Ondekane strongly condemned the bombing of areas under Jean
Pierre Bemba' s control which allegedly claimed over 500 lives.
</P>
<P>
''This shows what kind of a man Kabila is. He is an outlaw who
never respects his word,'' he said, adding that the RCD will only
trust the leaders of countries who signed the Lusaka cease-fire
agreement, and not President Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
