<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Plunging in Tokyo on Strong Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plummeted in Tokyo
Thursday for the second consecutive day as high-tech blue chips
continued their descent due to the strong yen.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 327.19 points, or 1.85
percent, from Wednesday's close ending at 17,358.19.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 28.65 points or 1.96 percent to 1,431.
02.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 494.22 million
shares from Wednesday's 472.49 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Materials Corp. was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
After opening at the day's high, the Nikkei index continued
sliding, following the previous day's trend of selling high-tech
blue chips, mainly electrical issues.
</P>
<P>
Major electrical issues fell substantially as the dollar
dropped to the 114 yen level, traders said.
</P>
<P>
They said retail sectors and others related to domestic
consumption, which were relatively strong amid Wednesday's plunge,
also turned downward.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers 1,036 to 195, with 80 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
