<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Expected to Grow 6.6 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in China's consumer
goods market is expected to grow by some 6.6 percent this year,
according to a report released today by the State Administration
of Internal Trade (SAIT).
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that retail sales of the whole society in the
first six months registered an increase of 9.9 percent in real
terms adjusted for deflation.
</P>
<P>
Guo Shouzhong, an SAIT official, said that the market situation
will be much better in the latter half of this year, as the market
enters a traditionally more brisk season, and government measures
to stimulate the economy, such as expanding investment, boosting
exports, and increasing incomes, begin to take effect.
</P>
<P>
Although the oversupply situation of most products remained
basically unchanged, sales of household electric appliances,
garments, food, telecommunications products and automobile
products still kept a hefty growth, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
Sales of these products will increase by a larger margin in the
latter half of this year, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
The report also reveals that the total sales of major
department stores in China hit 41.95 billion yuan, up 8.8 percent
from the same period last year. This was the first time since 1997
that department stores outpaced overall retail sales.
</P>
<P>
Chain stores continued to maintain an upbeat growth momentum
during the period. Currently, the number of chain stores in China
exceeds 1,500, and their sales surged in the first half by 31.7
percent over the same period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
