<HEADLINE> Jordan's King to Visit Lebanon for Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Abdullah Bin Hussein
is expected to make a two-day visit to Lebanon on September 14 to
seek ways of advancing the Middle East peace process, Lebanese
foreign ministry sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The king will hold talks with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud,
House Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime Minister Salim Hoss over the
prospects of the peace talks between Arabs and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
His visit carried "special significance" in light of the
imminent resumption of peace negotiations under Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak who has promised to resume all tracks of peace
talks during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
The king will also discuss the resettlement of Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon with Lebanese leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government has publicly rejected the resettlement
of the estimated 360,000 Palestinian refugees in the country for
fear the delicate sectarian balance would be disturbed.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Syria are among the countries that host a total of
nearly 4 million Palestinians who had fled their homeland since
the establishment of the Jewish state in 1948.
</P>
<P>
In addition to political issues, the two countries' leaders
would examine ways to bolster cooperation in various spheres, the
sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
