<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Animated Film Welcomed in Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- "Lotus Lantern," the first major
domestically produced animated film in China, has received a warm
welcome in this Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Although the film has been in theaters for less than a week,
about 17 thousand tickets have been sold at the Capital Cinema
alone.
</P>
<P>
"Ticket sales are much better than they were for Mulan, the
animation hit produced by Disney last year," said Xu Zhongren,
manager of the Capital Cinema.
</P>
<P>
Like the Disney film, Lotus Lantern is also derived from
traditional Chinese folklore, and describes how Little Chen Xiang
went down Huashan Mountain and saved his mother.
</P>
<P>
However, compared to other relatively inexpensive animated
movies, Lotus Lantern had a huge budget of 12 million yuan (about
1.44 million U.S. dollars). The producer, Shanghai Animated Film
Studio, spent four years making the film.
</P>
<P>
Many well-known film and screen stars including Jiang Wen, Ning
Jing, Chen Peisi, and Liang Tian were invited to be the voices of
the movie's characters, the first time this had been done in a
Chinese animated film.
</P>
<P>
Lotus Lantern was the result of a national call for domestic
animated films, which have long been cold-shouldered by Chinese
viewers in favor of foreign-made films which were flooding the
market.
</P>
<P>
"With the production of Lotus Lantern, we have come to a third
spring for Chinese cartoon movies, " said an official from the
State Administration for Radio, Film and Television. Chinese
animated movies had one prime in the late 1950s and early 1960s,
and another in the late 1970s and early 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Bonded Zone Lures Overseas Talent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ningbo Bonded Zone in the
coastal city of Ningbo in east China's Zhejiang Province will
introduce more talent from abroad as part of its effort to
maintain rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
Executives and experts in high-tech areas are especially
welcome to the zone, said Yao Li, director of the zone's
administration committee.
</P>
<P>
According to Yao, more than 40 people from overseas have
already applied for executive positions since the zone sent out a
public invitation for applications early this week.
</P>
<P>
The Ningbo Bonded Zone, established in 1992 with the approval
of China's State Council, is the only zone of its kind in the
province, mainly handling international trade, export-oriented
processing, and bonded storage services.
</P>
<P>
It now has more than 2,100 enterprises with registered capital
of over 1.2 billion U.S. dollars, 331 of which are overseas-funded
and involve 488 million U.S. dollars in total investment.
</P>
<P>
A 200,000-square-meter high-tech industrial park is taking
shape in the zone, which will focus on information technology,
machinery, and bio-engineering.
</P>
<P>
Ningbo is one of China's major coastal ports with many deep-
water berths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
