<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- An earthquake measuring 4.5 on the Richter
scale hit Argentina's San Juan and other northwest provinces at
noon on Wednesday .
</P>
<P>
The National Institute of Seismic Prevention said the tremor,
lasting some 30 to 40 seconds, did not leave any damage or victims.
The epicenter of the quake was at Sierra Pie de Palo, almost at
the center of the Province of San Juan. (Argentina-Earthquake)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- A group of U.S. military personnel are carrying out
combat training in the jungle area in eastern Ecuador, near the
shared border with Colombia, said an Ecuadorian military sources
on Wednesday who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The sources declined to reveal the number of the North
American "Jungle Brigade" and denied that the training in the
Ecuadorian Jungle Warfare School formed part of a U.S. plan of
intervention in Colombia to help fight the guerrilla groups. (
Ecuador-Military Training)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- A police helicopter crashed on Wednesday in Orlik in
the southern Czech Republic, killing two and injuring eight
special policemen on board.
</P>
<P>
Police authorities said the 10-passenger BO-105 helicopter
crashed around noon while on a training mission. The cause of the
accident is still under investigation. (Czech Replublic-Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The heat wave hitting the Midwest and the East in
the United States has led to the death of at least 263 people
since July 19, government officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21 states have registered heat-related deaths. There
have been 120 deaths in Illinois, followed by Missouri and Ohio
with 56 and 14 deaths respectively. (US-Heat Wave-Death)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The death toll in Monday's railway tragedy in West
Bengal of India rose to 288 Thursday with the recovery of one more
body from the mangled coaches of the two trains.
</P>
<P>
Northeastern Frontier Railway General Manager Rajendra Nath
said in Gaisal, West Bengal, that rescue operations were called
off early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
No more bodies were likely to be found in the debris, officials
said. All the bodies have been shifted from the accident site to
the morgues at local hospitals.(India-Accident-Toll)  
</P>
