<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Lifts Ban on Belgian Dairy Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
has lifted a ban on Belgian dairy products and derivatives.
</P>
<P>
But other Belgian products, including poultry, eggs, beef and
fodder, will remain embargoed till further notice, said Dr. Amin
Mohammed Yousif, director of the Food and Environment Control
Center of Abu Dhabi Municipality.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision made by the General Secretariat of UAE
Municipalities on Monday, dairy products from Belgium can now be
imported on submission of a certificate declaring that the
products are not contaminated by dioxin, a highly toxic chemical
that can cause cancer when absorbed by the body, the Khaleej Times
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The certificate must be issued by the Belgian government and
attested by the UAE embassy in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
"Following new developments in the Belgian food industry and
on recommendations of the the UAE Technical Committee for Food
Quality, the General Secretariat of Municipalities has decided to
lift the ban on Belgian food products made of milk and its
by-products," the decision said.
</P>
<P>
The ban imposed on poultry, eggs, beef and fodder will remain
in effect, it added.
</P>
<P>
The General Secretariat issued an order on June 5 banning
import of Belgian poultry, eggs, beef products and fodder,
following reports that food products in that country were
contaminated by dioxin.
</P>
<P>
Another order issued on June 6 extended the ban to include
dairy products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 08:14 </DATE_TIME>
