<HEADLINE> Manila Plans to Dredge Pasig River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government plans to
start dredging the Pasig River in Metro Manila in a week's time to
minimize the chances of flash floods in the area and nearby
provinces in the future.
</P>
<P>
A press statement released Thursday quoted President Joseph
Estrada as saying that this is one of the initial steps that the
government will implement to ensure flash flood not to wreak havoc
on the lives of residents again.
</P>
<P>
The Pasig River rehabilitation project includes flood control
program for the area of the lower Sanjuan River area. The
government will pursue a wide-scale reforestation and tree
planting program as part of its long-term solution to the flooding
problems.
</P>
<P>
The overflows due to rise of riverbed have reportedly
contributed to the disastrous flash flood, which has killed at
least 52, submerged some 300 villages and affected more than
111,519 families or 564,596 persons in central Luzon.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the project will get support from
the Overseas Economic Development Fund of Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
