<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Not to Visit Yasukuni Shrine on August 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi said Thursday he would not visit Tokyo's Yasukuni Shrine on
August 15, the 54th anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War
II.
</P>
<P>
"Taking the current circumstances into consideration, I will
not make a visit," Obuchi told reporters at his official residence.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka and eight other
cabinet ministers also said they would not visit the shrine.
</P>
<P>
"While understanding toward Yasukuni has not advanced in
neighboring countries, I will refrain from visiting on the 15th (
of August) so as not to cause unnecessary misunderstanding and
irritation as a member of the government," Nonaka told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura, Justice Minister Takao
Jinnouchi, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazwa, Education Minister
Akito Arima, International Trade and Industry Minister Kaoru
Yosano, Defense Agency chief Hosei Norota, Home Affairs Minister
Takeshi Noda and Economic Planning Agency chief Taichi Sakaiya
also have made clear that they would not visit the shrine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eight ministers including Environment Agency chief
Kenji Manabe and Transport Minister Jiro Kawasaki, however,
expressed their intention to visit the shrine, a bastion of the
wartime government-sponsored Shintoism and symbol of militarism in
Japan before and during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The shrine houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war
criminals, including wartime Prime Minister Hideki Tojo, and some
2.4 million Japanese military personnel and officials who died
since 1853 in Japan's various wars.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers' visits to the shrine have drawn criticism
from Asian countries and are also controversial because Japan's
postwar Constitution stipulates separation of the state and
religion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
