<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-nuclear Conference Closes in Hiroshima </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international anti-
nuclear conference ended Thursday in Hiroshima, western Japan,
with the adoption of a declaration calling for a nuclear-free 21st
century, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
About 280 anti-nuclear activists, including 60 people from 20
countries, attended the conference, hosted by the Japan Council
Against A and H Bombs (Gensuikyo).
</P>
<P>
The declaration called on all nuclear weapons states to commit
themselves to the elimination of nuclear weapons, renouncing the
policy of first use of such weapons, and stopping nuclear tests,
research and development.
</P>
<P>
It called for the "establishment, expansion and strengthening
of nuclear-free zones" in the world and also "making countries,
municipalities, ports and harbors nuclear-free."
</P>
<P>
The declaration also objected to expanded military alliances in
the world represented by new laws related to the updated Japan-U.S.
defense cooperation guidelines and a new strategic concept adopted
by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), which allows
NATO to intervene in conflicts outside of its member countries.
</P>
<P>
"These developments represent a dangerous departure from the
concept of the 'defense of allies,' which used to be the premise
of these military alliances," it said.
</P>
<P>
The conference urged the government of Japan -- the only
country to experience an atomic bombing in the world-- to "take
the initiative in ridding the world of nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
The gathering was the first of Gensuikyo's series of anti-
nuclear events until August 9 to commemorate the 54th anniversary
of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
