<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Major Parties Gear Up For Coming Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
...bargaining for."
</P>
<P>
The millennium's last general election tends to be a fierce
battle between the BJP led by Vajpayee and the Congress Party
headed by Sonia Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
For the Congress, it is the first chance to pit the untried and
untested Sonia Gandhi against a veteran politician who promised a
lot but palpably failed to deliver due to factors both within and
outside his rank.
</P>
<P>
For the BJP, it is the opportunity to sing paeans to the
caretaker prime minister who, the party asserted, led the country
to push "the intruders from Pakistan" out of Kargil and weaned
away the United States from Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Gearing up for the elections, the results of which are highly
unpredictable, the two rivals have stepped up attacks against each
other for nearly everything ranging from the recent Kashmir
conflict to telecommunications arrangements, from social problems
to political stability, and from past experiences to future
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
With no very big margin in strength for both sides, suave
advertising and public relations executives, glib spin-doctors and
shrewd party managers have come together to invent new images for
the two leaders and their parties.
</P>
<P>
In what promises to be a hi-tech election campaign, the
Congress has engaged three leading advertising agencies -- Sony,
Madison and Concept -- to drive home the message that it is the
best bet to run the country.
</P>
<P>
Its media strategy is expected to remind the people that the
BJP coalition was unstable from the day it came to power in March
last year, that the nuclear tests in last May had rendered South
Asia unstable and neutralized India's superiority over Pakistan,
that the Vajpayee government resorted to bombing in Kargil the day
Sonia took back her resignation as Congress president, thus
insinuating that it delayed taking action against "intruders"
because of political reasons.
</P>
<P>
With nothing matters more than Sonia Gandhi, the Congress'
media strategists hope to emphasize on her family lineage and
charisma, and describe the party's rejuvenation to her leadership.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the BJP is divided over hiring advertising
professionals to design its campaign and, insiders said, it has a
headstart over others because of the "feel good" factor and
obviously it plans to exploit Kargil for its electoral war against
the Congress.
</P>
<P>
BJP spokesman Arun Jetley claimed that the country had
appreciated the party and Vajpayee's performance, more so in
Kargil.
</P>
<P>
"Feel good" or not, insiders said that the BJP would launch a
scathing attack against Sonia Gandhi and her party, highlighting
her inexperience and her party's long legacy of corruption.
</P>
<P>
However, the Congress said, Kargil would be a major issue in
the elections and would have a negative impact on the BJP and its
allies.
</P>
<P>
As the two major parties entering into rivalry, Indian
corporations also face hard choices for either paying the bill for
or refusing contributions to the parties for their political
campaign, which will cost up to billions of rupees.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources here said, these parties were finding that
companies had drastically scaled down their contributions to their
campaign because of frequent general elections, possibility of
political uncertainty and a downturn in the industry over the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
"The industry seems to be tired of frequent elections and
coalition governments which are not able to take bold economic
decisions due to pulls and pressures from their constituent
parties," a Congress leader said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the election will be going on according to the
schedule announced last month by the Election Commission, which
made some minor changes in the original arrangements Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the new schedule, the first phase of polling would
now be held on September 5 instead of September 4 and the new
house will meet by October 21 as the dissolved Lok Sabha last met
on April 21 due to constitutional stipulation that the gap between
house sittings can not exceed six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Major Parties Gear Up for Coming Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Following the just-ended armed
conflict in the disputed Kashmir with neighboring Pakistan, major
parties in India have now geared up for another fierce struggle --
a campaign for the next general elections to the Lok Sabha, the
Lower House of parliament in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), winner of the last elections
in February 1998, is all set to formally launch its campaign here
on Sunday with a rally to be addressed by its steerer, the
caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
The BJP announced its first list of 138 candidates Tuesday,
which included three big men of the party: Vajpayee, Home Minister
L. K. Advani and Human Resource Development Minister Murli Manohar
Joshi.
</P>
<P>
BJP's rival the National Congress Party seems to be waiting for
the BJP's list of candidates before announcing its own one
following separate meetings of the Central Election Committee
(CEC) of both of the two parties Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The BJP's list includes 78 members of parliament of the
dissolved 12th Lok Sabha with only 11 women while the Congress'
CEC is expected to meet continuously for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Both the BJP and the Congress have been trying to sell a
stability plank following the two-month long conflict in Kargil of
Kashmir and, observers here said, the handling by the Vajpayee
government of the issue might affect the electoral prospects of
both parties.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Congress President Sonia Gandhi attacked the
Vajpayee government for "total failure" and "messing up of things"
particularly during the last three months, saying that Kargil and
the "stability factor" would be main election issues of her party.
</P>
<P>
While the Congress' manifesto and publicity campaign, being
given the final touches at present, promote the party's record of
providing stable and performing governments, the BJP is also not
lacking behind in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Despite heading a multi-party alliance of diverse ideologies,
the BJP is taking steps to dispel the impression that a coalition
can not run its full five-year term and provide a stable
government.
</P>
<P>
Following the downfall of its coalition last April, the BJP
managed to tie itself up with its ruling allies in a set-up called
the National Democratic Alliance (DNA) and has ever since tried to
project it as a cohesive entity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, after its failure to form a multi-party government
last April due to disagreement among the opposition, the strength
of the Congress further weakened in the following month when it
expelled three of its senior leaders for their objection against
Sonia Gandhi as the prime minister candidate because of her
Italian origin.
</P>
<P>
The coordination committee of the NDA decided last weekend to
issue a common manifesto which would promise to amend the
constitution to provide for a full five-year term for yet another
coalition government if it comes to power in October.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the BJP's attempts, the Congress has already started
attacking what was termed as "inherent weakness" of the NDA which,
it said, suits only for incoherent governance in return.
</P>
<P>
To a certain extent, what the Congress said might be reasonable
for the emergence of the first major trouble in the NDA on
Wednesday when muscle-flexing by BJP and its allies over
seat-sharing in the lower house elections came to the fore.
</P>
<P>
Hardly no smaller party in the NDA does not ask or hope for
more seats in the house with Samata Party led by Defense Minister
George Fernandes, which alongwith Lok Shakti has merged into
Janata Dal recently, demanding 55 seats.
</P>
<P>
A Samata spokesman said that it had one-fourth of the BJP's
strength and "we are asking for one-seventh of its strength now
(in the house), you can imagine what we are bargaining for."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
