<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12.3 Pct Youths Can Not Find Jobs in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 12 percent of New
Zealand youths between 20 and 24 could not find a job in the
second quarter of this year, a media release of Statistics New
Zealand said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The group had the second highest unemployment rate of 12.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The highest unemployment rate of 17.2 percent was recorded with
the age group of 15-to-19-year-olds, while the lowest rate of 3.9
percent was for those aged 55-64.
</P>
<P>
Also, fewer young people were holding jobs, according to the
New Zealand official statistical organization.
</P>
<P>
The number of 20-to-24-year-olds with jobs fell by 11,700 in
the year to June 1999, and the number of 15-to-19-year-olds
working fell by 6,800.
</P>
<P>
The overall jobless rate dipped to 7 percent in the second
quarter this year, the lowest rate since December 1997 and
compared with 7.6 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The number of people in work now is 1.74 million in the country
with a population of about 3.8 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
