<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Probes Wrangle in Congolese Rebel Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) --A Zambian delegation is in Goma in
the east of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to investigate
the wrangle within rebel Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD).
</P>
<P>
The delegation is led by Minister of State House Eric Silwamba,
the Zambia National Broadcasting Corporation, reported.
</P>
<P>
Due to the power struggle within the rebel movement, all the
rebel groups fighting to topple Congolese President Laurent Kabila
did not sign the cease-fire agreement, which was endorsed on July
10 by all the six warring countries involved in the one-year
conflict in Congo.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese Rally for Democracy split into two factions in
May this year -- one led by Emile Illunga and the other by Ernest
Wamba Dia Wamba who founded the RCD.
</P>
<P>
The RCD and the Movement for the Liberation for Congo (MLC) did
not sign the agreement then because of disagreement on who would
sign the deal on behalf of the RCD.
</P>
<P>
MLC leader Jean-Pierre Bemba later signed the cease-fire
agreement here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In May Ilunga ousted Wamba and was named by his supporters as
new leader of the RCD. After the wrangle broke out, Wamba moved
from Goma to Kisangani, the third largest city of Congo in the
north, and has been insisting that he is still the leader of the
rebel group.
</P>
<P>
Uganda backs both the faction led by Wamba and the MLC while
Rwanda backs the RCD faction led by Emile Illunga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
