<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloudy Weather Forecast for Eclipse Day in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Solar eclipse watchers in
Belgium were given another blow to their fully-intrigued hobby
when local meteorologists forecast cloudy weather for the days
leading up to their day of August 11.
</P>
<P>
The meteorologists of the Royal Institute of Meteorology of
Belgium predicted cloudy weather for the next five days right
prior to the total solar eclipse day next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As local transport authorities are preparing to cope with the
coming traffic congestion on local road systems prior to and on
the day of the eclipse, a rare phenomenon occurring at an interval
of 370 years on average, the solar eclipse watchers have to think
a second time before setting out for southern Belgium, where the
total eclipse was predicted to be visible.
</P>
<P>
Local eclipse watchers were already treated an earlier blow
when some 1,000 pairs of anti-retina burn glasses with defects
were found in Belgian shops.
</P>
<P>
The solar eclipse-oriented glasses, together with another 2,000
pairs for sale, were found to be defective after being imported
from Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Local health authorities appealed to the buyers of the
defective glasses not to use them on August 11 while witnessing
the solar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
Looking into the solar eclipse without protective glasses or
with defective glasses can cause serious eye problems such as
retina burns that may cause lasting damage, eye specialists warned.
</P>
<P>
Sales of solar eclipse glasses picked up a week ago when local
people started to prepare for the coming solar eclipse on August
11.
</P>
<P>
Solar eclipse watchers in Belgium were suggested to go to the
south of the country, especially to a town known as Virton to have
a better view of the rare phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
A solar eclipse happens when the moon travels right in between
the sun and the earth, blocking the view of the sun from the earth.
</P>
<P>
The August 11 solar eclipse is estimated to be visible in whole
or in part to around 2 billion residents of this planet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Inflation up by 2.4 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in Zambia has risen by
2.4 percent in July compared to the June increase of 1.9 percent
with the metropolitan low and high income group indices up by 1.8
percent and 3.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release from the Central Statistical
Office (CSO) available here Thursday, the sector that contributed
to observed inflation in July was the transport and communications
group.
</P>
<P>
The release said the transport and communications sectors
registered increases of 13.0 percent and 6.1 percent for the
metropolitan low and high income indices respectively which saw
year on year inflation increasing to 28.4 percent representing a
rise of 0.9 percentage points over the June figure.
</P>
<P>
The non metropolitan group transport index increased by 7.9
percent which saw an increase in coach fares whereas the price of
petroleum products, diesel and engine oil were up by 10 percent on
average nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The increase in petroleum products and subsequently came as a
result of the gutting of Indeni Oil Refinery in Ndola, Copperbelt
Province, a move which resulted in fuel shortage.
</P>
<P>
This has led to the government importing petrol, diesel and
other petroleum products from Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The fuel situation is expected to return to normal after the
completion of the 10-month renovations of the Ndola-based
refinery.
</P>
<P>
The release said the rent, fuel and lighting group recorded
increases of 3.5 and 2.1 percent for the metropolitan high and low
income groups respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
