<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Reforms Urged to Speed up in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has ordered the speedy execution of university reforms
recommended by a Presidential Task Force, the Presidential
Secretariat said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although steering committees were appointed in each university,
the progress of implementation of the reforms was very slow, the
secretariat said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Task Force appointed in May 1997 has
recommended key reforms, including the establishment of career
guidance units, restructuring of courses and examinations,
facilitation of cross disciplines and faculty combinations and the
introduction of new subject areas.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations also include the establishment of formal
links with research institutions and industrial and commercial
institutions for the development of undergraduate studies and
research collaboration.
</P>
<P>
The new curricula and courses should focus on the development,
economic and social needs of the country, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with university and educational officials, the
president stressed the importance of in-course assessments,
project work, tutorials, and staff development programs in all
universities.
</P>
<P>
At present there are 12 universities in Sri Lanka. Early in the
year, the government approved of establishing one more university
in the North Western Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
