<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Prisoners Threaten Hunger Strike Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Over 500 prisoners on treason
charges in Luzira Maximum Security Prison, the biggest prison in
Uganda, have threatened a hunger strike if their cases could not
be dealt with soon.
</P>
<P>
They are protesting against being kept on remand beyond the
mandatory 360 days and some of them have spent over two years on
remand without trial, the Monitor paper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In their letter to the Commissioner of Prisons Joseph Etima,
the inmates said that their hunger strike would begin from August
9. But it did not say how long the strike would last.
</P>
<P>
They argued that the government should free them if it could
not prosecute them in accordance with the Constitution provisions.
</P>
<P>
Etima admitted Wednesday that the prison has over 1,000 inmates
who have been on remand for between two and four years without
trial.
</P>
<P>
Those on treason charges were arrested in 1997 from West Nile
region in the northwestern part of the country and neighboring
countries while fighting the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners in this prison first staged a strike on July 22
this year and only relented after top prison authorities
intervened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
