<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Moves to Study Cause of Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
constituted an investigating committee to look into the landslide,
which caused disaster to residents in Antipolo and Rizal, a
presidential statement said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to spokesman Chito Slaud, the committee shall
determine the cause of the landslide and identify the parties, if
any, who may be held administratively, civilly or criminally
liable for the damage caused.
</P>
<P>
A disastrous landslide occurred Tuesday night with at least 14
persons killed, 50 houses destroyed and more than 50 persons
buried in the debris -- feared to be dead.
</P>
<P>
The committee, headed by Assistant Secretary Crispin Remulla of
the Presidential Management Staff, will have to submit its report
to President Joseph Estrada within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said Estrada will meet with housing officials
Thursday to discuss the safety problem of occupants of other
low-cost housing units in Antipolo.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado noted that an aerial
inspection showed many hills in Antipolo are being cleared to make
way for low-cost housing units.
</P>
<P>
Initial investigation by the National Disaster Coordinating
Council showed the landslide occurred at 7 p.m. Tuesday at the
Cherry Hill subdivision. The landslide buried 25 houses and
damaged 378 others, displacing 125 families.
</P>
<P>
The flash flood starting last Sunday hit Metro Manila and its
nearby provinces, and affected 111,519 families or 564,596
persons.
</P>
<P>
At least 52 persons were confirmed dead, 31 injured and 11
missing in flash flood triggered by massive downpour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
