<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebel Leader Accuses Kabila of Breaking Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Congolese President Laurent
Kabila has been accused by a rebel leader of breaking the
recently-signed Lusaka cease-fire accord when a Sudanese plane
allegedly bombed two northern fishing towns in the country
Wednesday, killing more than 500 people.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Bemba, a millionaire businessman who heads the
Uganda-backed Congolese Liberation Movement, said this attack
shattered the peace deal he had signed just three days earlier,
the New Vision daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
One Russian-built Sudanese Antonov plane dropped 18 bombs on
the two rebel-held towns of Makanza and Bogbonga on the Congo
River about 800 kms northeast of the capital Kinshasa, the rebel
leader was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of those killed were civilians. About 134 rebels fighting
to out Kabila were also killed in the surprise attack, he noted,
adding that he had already informed Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba, who mediated the peace accord, of the attack.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Bemba endorsed a peace pact worked out in the
Zambian capital last month which was agreed by six African
governments involved in the year-old war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
