<HEADLINE> Mexico Beats Brazil 4-3 to Win Confederations Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 4 (Xinhua) -- In a major soccer upset,
Miguel Zepeda broke a second-half tie with his second goal as
Mexico beat Brazil 4-3 to win the Confederations Cup soccer
tournament on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Jose Manuel Abundis and Cuauhtemoc Blanco also scored for
Mexico. Brazil's goals came from Serginho, Roni and Ze Roberto.
</P>
<P>
Mexico controlled the first half. In the 12th minute, Zepeda
made a hard drive that bounced off goalkeeper Dida's hands and
over his head into the net.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's second goal came in the 27th minute, when Abundis got
all alone in the right side of the penalty box and fired in a pass
from Blanco.
</P>
<P>
Brazil began to fire up toward the end of the first half. In
the 43rd minute, after German Villa tripped up Ronaldinho as he
tried to shoot, Serginho made a penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
And in the first minute of the second half, Ronaldinho passed
across the penalty box to an open Roni, who made an easy goal and
tied the score at 2.
</P>
<P>
Mexico took the lead again in the 48th minute, when Zepeda
drove in a tip from Abundis. And in the 61st minute, Blanco
dribbled around defenders and crossed a shot into the net.
</P>
<P>
But only a minute later, Roni centered a pass to Ze Roberto,
who drove it into the goal to make the score 4-3.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's young team made it to the final with an impressive
first round, shutting out Germany, the United States and New
Zealand. It edged Saudi Arabia 8-2 in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Mexico defeated Bolivia and Saudi Arabia and tied Egypt in the
first round, then advanced to the final with a 1-0 overtime
victory over the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
