<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Install Differentiate Global Positioning System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
taken a scheme to install a differentiate global positioning
system (DGPS) to determine exact position of marine vessels,
off-shore objects and aircraft through the satellite data.
</P>
<P>
The 220 million taka (about 4.44 million U.S. dollars) project,
financed by the World Bank, will be implemented by the Bangladesh
Inland Water Transport Authority, The Bangladesh Observer daily
newspaper Thursday quoted officials of the Ministry of Shipping as
saying.
</P>
<P>
If implemented, it will replace the four-decade old "Dacca
(Dhaka) Chain System" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The DGPS is a satellite-based ultra-modern electronic device to
find three dimensional positions -- latitude, longitude and
altitude -- of the distant off-shore objects with approximately 99
percent accuracy by using the reserved low-frequency radio
signals, and it will also provide velocity and time related
information ofe
implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
