<HEADLINE> Postage Stamps Celebrate Macao's Return To China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The designs of postage stamps
being used to mark Macao's return to the motherland on December 20
have been decided and the stamps are being printed, according to
officials at the Postal Bureau's Stamp Distribution Bureau.
</P>
<P>
They are an 8-yuan (96 U.S. cents) stamp with a picture of Deng
Xiaoping, chief architect of China's reform, and "one country, two
systems", his government policy, with a scene of people of Macao
celebrating the return with a dragon dance, the Macao Bridge, and
the People's Bank of China in the background, a 1.5-yuan stamp
with pictures of the Basic Law of the Macao Special Administrative
Region and the Great Wall, and 0.5 yuan stamp with a picture of
the Sino-Portugese Joint Statement on Macao and the lotus, the
region's flower.
</P>
<P>
The designers were Yang Wenqing, a noted stamp designer of the
Postal Bureau, and Zhang Guilin, a professor at the Central
Academy of Fine Arts. They say that they wanted to use Deng
Xiaoping's "one country, two systems" policy to represent the
eagerness of the Macao people to return to the embrace of the
motherland and the region's great prospects.
</P>
<P>
The stamps will be officially released on December 20. 
