<HEADLINE> Czech Car Export Doubles in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic exported 402,
000 cars in 1998, a 102 percent increase compared with that of
1997, showed the latest figure from the Ministry of Industry and
Trade.
</P>
<P>
The car export totaled 66.1 billion Czech Koruna (34 Koruna =
one U.S. dollar) last year, and increased by 53 percent over 1997.
The car, which made up 7.8 percent of the total export volume last
year, has become Czech's competitive products for foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Germany was the biggest importer of Czech cars in 1998,
followed by Slovakia and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for Skoda Car Plant said that the cheap but good
Skoda brand cars continued to be in great demand, adding the
company sold 199,000 Skoda cars in the first half of this year, a
10.6 percent rise over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Skoda car export to Germany and Britain in the first half of
this year increased by 40.4 and 67.5 percent respectively over the
same period of last year. The export to the central and east
European countries also grew sharply this year.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, only 39,000 Skoda cars were sold at home,
dropping 12.6 percent. The economic recession and sagging domestic
demand is blamed for the decline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
