<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andorra Passes New Laws Against Cigarette Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Andorra has adopted new laws to
further curb once-rampant smuggling of cigarettes out of the
European principality, the European Commission (EC) said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation includes a law on frauds in customs matters,
a law on the control of sensitive goods, and one modifying the
Penal Code by introducing smuggling as an offense.
</P>
<P>
The new laws are regarded as further legal steps to fight
against smuggling of cigarettes out of the country. In 1996, the
small, 468-square kilometer country situated between France and
Spain was identified as one of the main sources of smuggled
cigarettes in the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The EC, executive organ of the EU, said it had close
consultations with Andorra before the latter took the legal steps.
</P>
<P>
For some time, large quantities of cigarettes have been
smuggled out of Andorra. As a result, EU countries lost 400
million euros (428 million U.S. dollars) in 1997 alone.
</P>
<P>
However, thanks to the effective legal and administrative
measures taken by Andorra, and collaboration with its neighboring
countries, cigarette smuggling decreased markedly in 1998, the EC
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Cigarette smuggling has been carried out on large scales by
international criminal rings. Smuggled cigarettes have markets in
Andorra's neighboring countries and even in Britain and Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina to Eliminate Protectionist Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem promised here Wednesday that his government would eliminate
resolution 911, which regulates the application of trade
safeguards.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of eliminating the safeguards, which were enacted
by the Latin American Association of Integration ALADI) against
imports from Brazil, is to defend the interests of the regional
bloc of the South American Common Market (Mercosur) comprising
Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay. Menem said,
</P>
<P>
The new ruling, which was made between the presidents of
Argentina and Brazil in July, will take effect on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the face of losses provoked by the devaluation of the
Brazilian currency, the real, the Argentine government adopted the
resolution, which established safeguards against Brazilian exports
of textiles, footwear and electronic equipment in order to protect
its national industries.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the resolution, however, brought protests from
the Brazilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
