<HEADLINE> Sotomayor Confirmed Positive on Dismal Pan Am Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The 13th Pan American
Games on Wednesday saw its first high-profile athlete failing a
drug test and having his gold medal stripped off.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's high-jumping world record holder Javier Sotomayor has
been confirmed here today to test positive for Cocaine following
his fourth Pan Am gold medal on last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The world and Olympic champion became the third athlete of the
Winnipeg Games to give a positive result following Canada's roller
hockey goaltender Steve Vezina and Dominican woman high jumper
Juana Rosario Arrendel, and obviously the most sensational one.
</P>
<P>
But the world and Olympic champipon himself said through the
Cuban delegation that he is totally innocent and would appeal the
Pan American Sports Organization (PASO) decision to withdraw the
gold medal from him.
</P>
<P>
Cuba acted defiantly by declaring Sotomayor is "an innocent and
dignified man" who has never taken any banned drugs and accusing
there exists some kind of sabotage and conspiracy against the
Cuban athletes.
</P>
<P>
The Sotomayor Affair overshadowed today's Pan Am arena where
the hosts Canada racked up a total of eight gold to surpass the
seven from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Their men's field hockey team thrilled the whole country by
upsetting the defending champions Argentina 1-0 in the final to
capture the gold.
</P>
<P>
In the men's beach volleyball final, the Canadian duo of Jody
Holden and Conrad Leinemann Brazil also did it a hard way,
toughing out a 12-8, 11-12, 13-11 win over the mighty Brazilian
pair of Adriano and Lula.
</P>
<P>
The women's field hockey title went to the defending champions
Argentina, who cruised to a 5-2 easy win over the United States,
while Brazilian pair of Behar and Bede thrashed American
partnership Jennifer Pavley and Marsha Miller 12-5, 12-0 to
triumph in the women's beach volleyball final.
</P>
<P>
Brazil made a big splash in the Pan Am Pool here today as a
pair of Games record fell to them (Fernando Scherer of men's 100m
freestyle and Leonardo Costa of men's 200m backstroke) on Day
Three of the swimming competitions.
</P>
<P>
The United States continued to occupy the top spot of the
medals standings with a total of 83 golds, with inspired Canada (
47) edging close second-placed Cuba (49). 
</P>
</TEXT>
