<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Again Vows to Veto Republican Tax Cut Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
vowed again on Wednesday to veto a Republican tax cut proposal of
792 billion U.S. dollars, but indicated he was open to a
compromise deal.
</P>
<P>
"If they conclude this plan and send it to me I will have to
veto it," Clinton said of the plan worked out by a committee of
House and Senate Republicans on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I will refuse to sign any plan that signs away our commitment
to America's future, Social Security, Medicare, paying down the
debt," he told reporters in the White House Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and most Democrats have said that any cut over 300
billion dollars would be unacceptably risky to the nation's
economic future.
</P>
<P>
The Republican plan for the deepest tax reduction since 1981
would cut taxes by 792 billion dollars over the next 10 years,
compared to a Clinton proposal for 250 billion dollars in tax cuts
over a decade.
</P>
<P>
The White House has said the Republican plan is too large and
would require either steep budget cuts or raids on money set aside
for Social Security. Clinton has repeatedly vowed to veto it.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he was still willing to seek an agreement with
Congress, Clinton said, "I hope we can reach an agreement. I'm
willing to work for it and hope we can achieve it."
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders said the vote would come up for final
passage this week but the plan would not be sent to Clinton for
signature until after the August congressional recess. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
