<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sotomayor Fails Drugs Test, Gold Medal Taken Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Cuban high jump world
record holder Javier Sotomayor tested positive for banned drugs
cocaine and would been stripped of gold medal won in the Pan-
American Games last week, officials at the Pan American Games
revealed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The news means Sotomayor cannot go defend his crown at the
World Championships in Seville, Spain, later this month.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Pan American Sports Organisation (ODEPA),
Mario Vasques Rana, said Sotomayor, 31, will face a two-year
suspension from competitions.
</P>
<P>
Primo Nebiolo, president of the International Amateur Athletic
Federation (IAAF), said: "I can't understand it. I feel bad for
him."
</P>
<P>
Sotomayor, 31, regarded as one of athletics' greats, won the
world title in 1997 and took the Olympic crown in 1992.
</P>
<P>
He also won gold at the the 1993 world championships and took
silver in the 1991 and 1995 events.
</P>
<P>
His world record stands at 2.45 meters.
</P>
<P>
Pan Am high jump gold medals instead go to Canadians Kwaku
Boateng and Mark Boswell, with Charles Clinger of the United
States taking the bronze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
