<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Javier Sotomayor Factfile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Following is the
factfile on Cuban high jumper Javier Sotomayor who tested positive
for cocaine at the Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
1967 - Born in Limonar, state of Matanzas, Cuba
</P>
<P>
1982 - At the age of 15, clears two meters for the first time
</P>
<P>
1985 - Makes his first major mark internationally, finishing
second in the world championships.
</P>
<P>
1987 - Wins his first Pan American Games gold medal in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
1988 - Sets world record for first time with jump of 2.43
meters.
</P>
<P>
1989 - Breaks world record again, this time with a jump of 2.44,
making him the first man to clear eight feet. Claims his first of
four world indoor titles.
</P>
<P>
1991 - Wins second successive Pan American gold in Havana.
</P>
<P>
1992 - Wins gold at Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
1993 - Breaks his own world record by jumping 2.45, a mark that
still stands. Wins his first world outdoor championship in
Stuttgart, Germany.
</P>
<P>
1994 - Wins gold in the World Cup
</P>
<P>
1995 - Wins his third successive Pan American Games gold in Mar
del Plata, Argentina
</P>
<P>
1997 - Wins his second world championships gold in Athens
</P>
<P>
1999 - Becomes the first athletics competitor to win four
successive Pan American Games gold medals, only to be stripped of
the title because of doping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increases Anti-flood Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to increase its
investment in water conservancy projects this year, creating flood-
control projects along its major rivers downstream and erosion-
control projects upstream, a leading water official said.
</P>
<P>
Following last year's drastically increased expenditure on
Yangtze embankments, which has already shown some remarkable
benefits during this year's flood season, the central government
is considering adding 10 billion yuan (about 1.2 billion U.S.
dollars) in funds earmarked for the construction of water
conservancy projects, Minister of Water Resources Wang Shucheng
was quoted by Thursday's China Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The additional funds are scheduled to be allocated soon after
this year's flood season, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government will increase funds in river embankment
consolidation projects in Hunan, Hubei, Jiangxi, and Anhui
provinces this year, and reinforcement projects along the Yangtze
river are to be completed in three to five years.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, part of the investment will be used to
intensify efforts to control soil erosion, China's top
environmental issue plaguing over two thirds of the country's
territory, particularly the worsening erosion of the upper reaches
of major rivers.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration of soil erosion, partially caused by
excessive logging on the upper reaches of the rivers, has been
blamed as one of the major factors causing last summer's
devastating flooding along the Yantse in the south and the Songhua
River in the northeast.
</P>
<P>
Wang urged localities to further intensify their erosion-
control by "seizing the opportunity of the central government's
strong financial support this year to build 'a beautiful Northwest
China,' as President Jiang Zemin has instructed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
