<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Exchange Reserves Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's net foreign reserves
decreased to 16.11 billion U.S. dollars in the week ending July
30, from 16.14 billion dollars in the previous week, Bank
Indonesia said in its latest weekly report.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the decrease in the country's net
foreign reserves to the repayment of foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Net international reserves were still above the 14.7-billion-
dollar target set by the International Monetary Fund, the report
was quoted by The Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gross international reserves -- net foreign exchange reserves
plus outstanding foreign exchange contracts -- also decreased by
31.5 million dollars to 26.59 billion dollars, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Govt Simplifies Investment Procedures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Wednesday decided to drastically simplify investment procedures
and offer wide ranging incentives, including provision of tax
holidays, to attract capital investment, especially from overseas.
</P>
<P>
"President B.J. Habibie fully supports the moves to be taken by
state minister for investment, and has called them very
progressive and very revolutionary," Information Minister Yunus
Yosfiah said after a cabinet meeting on economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has witnessed a sharp drop in investment levels of
both domestic and overseas investors following the prolonged
social unrest that has engulfed the country since the fall of
former president Soeharto in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The recently concluded peaceful, free and transparent general
elections seem to have failed to attract fresh investment capital.
</P>
<P>
The new investment policy will then be embodied within a new
presidential decree set to issue in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The proposed decree provides tax holidays as well as authorizes
Indonesian embassies and consulate general offices overseas to
issue preliminary approval to investors wishing to invest capital
in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign investors are now free to come directly to the
Investment Coordination Board office, or to Indonesian embassies
and consulate general offices located overseas," Yunus was quoted
by The Indonesian Observer Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The provincial and regional investment boards will also be
authorized to issue permits to would-be investors, domestic and
overseas, he said.
</P>
<P>
"President Habibie has also decided that presidential approval
is not needed for new investment as was previously the case," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The minister also disclosed the presence of critical views
raised by other ministers during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Farid Anfasa Moeloek said, for example, that
new investment should be environment friendly, and should not
cause damage to those living near investment sites.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Development Supervision and State
Administrative Reform Hartarto suggested that in view of the
population density of the Java island, any new investment policy
should aim to promote investment outside Java where areas remain
relatively sparsely populated and lacking in investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
