<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China's Forests expected To Recover Within 50 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A massive forest protection
campaign of the Ministry of Forestry is expected to help forests
in China's Greater Hinggan Mountains to return to normal in about
50 years, according to Dai Wanchun, deputy general manager of the
Timber Group.
</P>
<P>
Heavy logging has taken a toll on this part of northeast China.
Over 100 million cubic meters of timber have been felled for the
state since 1965, a tenth of the nation's total timber output, and
the rapid growth in population there has reduced forest resources
from over 520 million cubic meters to just some 170 million cubic
meters now.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that the area will add another million hectares of man-
made forests, increasing forest coverage from 74 percent now to 83
percent in 2010 to provide healthier forest resources by mid-21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The central government began an ambitious forest protection
project after last year's heavy flooding on the Yangtze, Nenjiang,
and Songhua rivers, limiting or stopping logging of State-owned
forest areas along the upper and middle reaches of the Yangtze and
the Yellow rivers.
</P>
<P>
And 75 percent of the over six million hectares in the Greater
Hinggan Mountains were included in the project's first-phase,
reducing timber output to 2.14 million cubic meters by the end of
2000, or 38 percent less than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Central government and the commercial banks will also
allocate funds to help the 220,000 lumbermen in forest areas
change their work to afforestration, forest protection, and other
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
