<HEADLINE> U.S. Death Toll in Heat Wave Reaches 263 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The heat wave hitting the
Midwest and the East in the United States has led to the death of
at least 263 people since July 19, government officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21 states have registered heat-related deaths. There
have been 120 deaths in Illinois, followed by Missouri and Ohio
with 56 and 14 deaths respectively.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, U.S. President Bill Clinton earmarked 55 million U.
S. dollars in federal aid to help residents of nine Southern and
Midwestern states cope with the heat.
</P>
<P>
The money, provided under a program that is used more often to
help low-income people pay for heat during the winter, may be used
to buy air conditioners, fans and other relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
