<HEADLINE> Manila Imposes Price Control Amid Flash Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
imposed price control on basic commodities in flood-hit Metro
Manila and nearby provinces for 60 days to curb market blackmail,
the newspaper Malaya reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Wednesday's convention of the National
Price Coordinating Councils, which was chaired by Trade Secretary
Jose Pardo.
</P>
<P>
The trade secretary said prices of basic commodities will be
based on the prevailing prices prior to the onset of the calamity.
</P>
<P>
Aside from Metro Manila, areas covered by the price control are
provinces of Rizal, Pampanga and Pangasinan, all of them having
been declared under a state of calamity.
</P>
<P>
Teams will be established to monitor prices, ensure adequate
supply, and intensify the price tag law and price ceilings, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
Reports said prices of fish and vegetables in Metro Manila have
risen by 20 pesos (about 0.5 U.S. dollar) per kilogram. Things
were even worse in some nearby provinces as some basic commodities
have increased by 100 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
