<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Voter registration in East Timor has been
extended by two days until Friday for more people to participate
in the legal activity to determine the future of the territory,
the United Nations announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-day registration process was due to end Wednesday, but U.
N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan authorized the extension, his
spokesman said. (UN-East Timor)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq Wednesday criticized the U.N. Sanctions
Committee for blocking contracts Iraq signed with foreign
companies under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
A total of 457 Iraqi contracts worth 756 million U.S. dollars
signed under the fifth phase of the oil-for-food program are still
blocked by the U.N. Sanctions Committee, said an Iraqi Trade
Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said in a statement carried by the Iraqi
News Agency that Iraq held American and British representatives in
the United Nations committee responsible for hampering the
endorsement of those contracts. (Iraq-UN-Contracts)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council on Wednesday
extended a welcome to a report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, saying that the 15-nation body will "provide active support
" to the peace agreement, which ended conflicts in the Western
African country of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
Security Council, Martin Andjaba of Namibia, said, "Members of the
Council expressed their determination to provide active support to
the Lome Peace Agreement," which was signed in July in Togo.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Council met in a closed-door
session to discuss a report from Annan, who wants to see a bigger
U.N. presence in Sierra Leone. (UN-Annan-Sierra Leone)
</P>
<P>
---
