<HEADLINE> Jones, Kipketer Lead Golden League Jackpot Chase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Marion Jones of the United States
and Wilson Kipketer of Denmark kept their strong momentum to chase
the one million dollars jackpot on offer as they powered to
convincing wins at the Monaco Golden League Meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gabriela Szabo of Romania and Bernard Barmasai of Kenya are the
other two who also won their races to kept themselves in the
running for the end of season prize.
</P>
<P>
Jones, 23, clocked a time of 22.15 seconds and claimed her 20th
consecutive 200 meters victory at the Golden League Meeting.
</P>
<P>
World 800m record holder Kipketer is storming back to form
after a bout of malaria as he clocked a time of one minute, 42.57
seconds which is the best of the year.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Szabo, the 5,000-meter world champion, ran a
brilliant 3,000-meter race, winning in a time of 8:28.36.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai also savored the victory as the 25-year-old world
record holder dominated the 3,000-meter steeplechases race and
reached a seasonal best time of 7:58.98 for his fourth straight
race win.
</P>
<P>
The Golden League series jackpot is shared by those athletes
who win the same event in all seven meets. Herculis is the fourth
in the series with the next event in Zurich on August 11.
</P>
<P>
In a quick 200-meter race, in-form Maurice Greene clocked his
fastest time of the year 19.92 seconds to hold off a challenge
from Frankie Fredericks of Namibia one hundredth of a second
behind. Obadele Thompson of Barbados was third in 20.11.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Violeta Szekely was another winner as she cruised to
the fastest time of the year, 4:01.49, in the women's 1,500-meter
race.
</P>
<P>
The 34-year-old Romanian was out of competition for three years
after a positive drugs test at the 1995 world indoor championships.
</P>
</TEXT>
