<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Latin American economic growth
slowed down in 1998 due to the influence of the international
financial crisis and natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America and
the Caribbean region (ECLA) said Wednesday in a report that
regional economic growth fell from 5.4 percent in 1997 to 2.3
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report also said the regional Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
will recover in the second half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Foreign capital earnings shrank to 68 billion U.S. dollars in
1998 from 85 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the region hovered around 60 billion
dollars in 1998, but bonds, bank loans and stock shares suffered a
steep decline.
</P>
<P>
The majority of South American countries registered a fall in
GDP. The economy of Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Paraguay,
Peru and Venezuela fell between 3-4 percent in 1998 compared to
1997, ECLA said.
</P>
<P>
The regional inflation rate was about 10 percent in the 12
months until June of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's inflation rate reached 31 percent and Ecuador's was
more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The average unemployment rate increased from 7.5 percent in the
first half of 1998, to 8.5 percent in the same period in 1999, the
highest one in the decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
