<HEADLINE> Panamanian-Colombian Border Under Police Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The border zone between
Panama and Colombia has been placed under police control,
Panamanian Minister of Government and Justice Mariela Sagel said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian government has sent a contingent of frontier
police to the eastern province of Darien, close to the border,
following complaints from the Colombian military authorities that
the border zone between the two countries has become a transfer
area of weapons, supposedly coming from Central America.
</P>
<P>
Sagel admitted that there had been shootings between the
Panamanian police and armed groups, but he did not confirm whether
or not the shootings involved paramilitary or guerrillas from the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC).
</P>
<P>
Press reports on Wednesday said there were violent clashes
between the Colombian Army and the FARC in the Colombian province
of Uraba, close to the Panamanian border. Between 15 and 40
guerrillas were killed in the clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
