<HEADLINE> Colombian President Distinguishes Wars Against Drugs and Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Andres Pastrani Wednesday differentiated the war against drug
trafficking and that against the guerrillas in the country during
his meeting with the U.S. Chief of the "South Command," General
Charles Wilhelm.
</P>
<P>
"Colombia is facing two distinctly different wars: the war
against drug traffickers, who are not only threatening the country
but also the world, and the conflict with the guerrilla movement,
which imperils social order," elaborated the president.
</P>
<P>
He said that "it is possible to hold a dialogue with the
guerrillas to construct a third phase of democracy to untie the
principal knots of social order and put an end to the political
violence."
</P>
<P>
Wilhelm, who is on an official visit to Colombia, attended a
ceremony to create a "river brigade" of 3,000 members, which is
divided into five river battalions and one special forces unit.
The ceremony was held on Wednesday in the southern city of Puerto
Leguizamo. 
</P>
