<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christie: "I'm Completely Innocent" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- English sprinter Linford Christie
insisted Wednesday he was "completely innocent" and vowed to clear
his name after UK Athletics revealed he had failed a drugs test.
</P>
<P>
The sport's governing body revealed that Christie tested
positive for the banned substance nandrolone at an indoor meeting
in Dortmund on February 13.
</P>
<P>
Christie has been suspended pending a disciplinary hearing but
The British 100 meters gold medallist at the Barcelona Olympics in
1992 vowed to "clear his name one way or another" and called for
an investigation into the current drug-testing system.
</P>
<P>
"I am completely innocent of any wrongdoing and any case
against me will be vigorously defended," said 39-year-old Christie.
</P>
<P>
"I have consistently opposed the use of banned substances by
athletes and it is ridiculous to imagine that I would take them
after my retirement.
</P>
<P>
"I agree that there should be a full investigation into the
numerous cases where metabolites of nandrolone have been found in
urine samples to establish how this could happen without the
knowledge of the athlete.
</P>
<P>
"They are test results. If they say they found something, they
found something. I can't dispute that.
</P>
<P>
"Some people are asking me where does it come from? I can't
tell you where it comes from."
</P>
<P>
"But I'm not upset about it because I'm innocent. If I was
guilty, then I would be upset and worried about it.
</P>
<P>
"But at the end of the day, I'm going to clear my name, one way
or another. Mistakes have been made. When I first heard it was a
quite shock but the truth will come out in the end. I've never
done it (take drugs) and I never will do it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
