<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico, Venezuela Renew Pact on Providing Oil to Central America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Mexico and
Venezuela renewed on Wednesday the San Jose Agreement on
providing petroleum under favorable terms to 11 nations in Central
America and the Caribbean region.
</P>
<P>
In their respective capitals, Mexican Presidents Ernesto
Zedillo and his Venezuelan counterpart Hugo Chavez signed the
documents for the renewal of the agreement, officially named the "
Program of Energy Cooperation for Central America and the
Caribbean."
</P>
<P>
The San Jose Agreement has been renewed on an annual basis ever
since it was formulated on August 3, 1980, in the Costa Rican
capital from where it took its name.
</P>
<P>
Both Mexico and Venezuela supply 80,000 barrels of petroleum
under favorable terms on a daily basis to Barbados, Belize, Costa
Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala, Haiti, Honduras, Jamaica, Nicaragua,
Panama and the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
Some of the crude supplied to these countries under the San
Jose Agreement receives 20 to 25 percent subsidies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0378 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Retailers Feeling E-commerce Bite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A new report released
Wednesday shows that traditional brick and mortar retailers in the
United States will begin to feel the bite from e-commerce soon.
</P>
<P>
Less than 10 percent of e-commerce revenue in 2002 will be from
incremental sales, according to the report from U.S. research firm
Jupiter Communications. This means that the bulk of the growth in
e-commerce will come from sales that would have taken place
off-line.
</P>
<P>
Of the 11.9 billion U.S. dollars in online commerce Jupiter is
predicting for 1999 in the United States, only 720 million
dollars, or six percent, will come from sales that would not have
otherwise taken place.
</P>
<P>
Jupiter estimates that the percentage of incremental sales will
grow only slightly, to 6.5 percent, or three billion dollars of
the expected 41 billion dollars, by 2002, with growth dependent on
merchants' ability to target offers and promotions.
</P>
<P>
The new research urges traditional merchants to build unified
ventures that take advantage of their off-line assets -- an
existing customer base, a trusted brand name, customer data, and
sales and distribution infrastructure. Otherwise, the research
firm said, they will risk losing sales to Internet-only merchants.
</P>
<P>
"With a few notable exceptions," the research firm said,
"traditional merchants' Internet strategies have been paralyzed by
indecision, and the merchants continue to watch Web upstarts seize
the early momentum."
</P>
<P>
Jupiter said that companies need to accept the Internet as
another channel for their business or risk losing sales to
competitors. "Building a Web site isn't really an option for
traditional merchants. It's something that they've absolutely got
to do," the research firm said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0379 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Corn Growers Call for Action to Address Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 4 (Xinhua) -- American farmers Wednesday
called on the government to take action to address their economic
concerns.
</P>
<P>
The National Corn Growers Association (NCGA) chronicled in a
statement the decline in corn prices over the past few years, from
3.24 U.S. dollars per bushel for 1995, to 2.71 dollars for 1996,
2.43 dollars for 1997, 1.95 dollars for 1998, and a projected
1.65-2.05 dollars for 1999.
</P>
<P>
NCGA quoted its chairman Ryland Utlaut as saying that the U.S.
farmers continue to support a market-oriented approach to farm
policy -- an approach that allows farmers to make the basic
production decisions for their operations. But "There are other
factors that need to fall into place."
</P>
<P>
He cited affordable, effective crop insurance tools, access to
world market, research efforts and an efficient transportation
system. "Given the current state of the farm economy, there's
clearly a need for assistance," Utlaut said. "Farmers need
immediate aid to help them weather the current crisis."
</P>
<P>
Among the actions NCGA urged the government to take are
short-term relief, changes to the marketing assistance loan
program to ensure that a producer's full production is eligible
for loan deficiency payments, efforts to build export market
including reform of U.S. sanctions policies and China's admission
into the WTO.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990805.0380 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved
lower Wednesday as investors remained in belief that the Federal
Reserve would raise interest rates to prevent the U.S. economy
from inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 2.54 at
10,674.77. The blue chip index was pushed higher in the session
earlier by the news of merger between Dow Chemical and Union
Carbide for 9.3 billion U.S. dollars but gave up all the gain of
152 points in the final half-hour of trading.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 16.85 at 1,305.33 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 47.99 at 2,540.00.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 7.94 at 614.46 and the
American Stock Exchange index fell 3.52 at 776.95. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.58 at 429.70.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,008 down, 1,008 up and 516
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 781.24 million shares from 729.36
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
